{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Es9TDQPf3NedsZAii36MzQ","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me provide the architectural review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Architecture & Design — Title Extractor Iteration 28\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, ~1660 lines)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe four fixes are mechanically sound and accurately match the improvement plan's intent. The `buildCandidates` return type change threads cleanly through the pipeline. The main architectural tension is in Fix 4 (unified prologue detector): the new `isContinuation` predicate substantially overlaps with `isProse`, and the combination produces a more permissive gate than stated in the plan's risk section. There is also an unresolved inconsistency between where `applyBlindOcrRepair` is called in `normalizeOcrTitle` (always uses `l`-variant for mixed-case) versus the new dual-variant approach used during candidate generation (which correctly defers to the embedding scorer). This is a post-selection inconsistency, not a candidate-generation bug, but it means a title selected via the correct `i`-variant can be corrupted back to `l` on output.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 1. `normalizeOcrTitle` still uses `l`-variant for mixed-case output\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:958`\n\n**Impact**: Fix 1 correctly generates both `i` and `l` variants during candidate generation and lets the embedding scorer pick the better one. But `normalizeOcrTitle` at line 958 calls `applyBlindOcrRepair(text)`, which internally routes mixed-case text through `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"l\")` — the `l`-variant. If the embedding scorer selects the `i`-variant (`Braised Cod with White Wine`), that exact string reaches `normalizeOcrTitle`. The string no longer contains any `1` artifacts, so `applyBlindOcrRepair` is a no-op for it — this specific case is actually fine. But if the raw OCR text itself is what wins (the non-repaired form with `1` artifacts), `normalizeOcrTitle` will apply the wrong substitution.\n\nThe root issue is that `normalizeOcrTitle` is called on `s.text` at lines 1631 and 1636, and `s.text` is the candidate string that won scoring. If a raw-form candidate (`Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`) somehow wins over both variants (e.g., when candidate cap is hit and only the raw form is retained), `normalizeOcrTitle` will produce `Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `applyBlindOcrRepair` was refactored to be the single shared implementation (good), but it still hardcodes `l` for mixed-case. The `normalizeOcrTitle` path was not updated to use the `i`-variant logic.\n\n**Solution**: Either (a) change `applyBlindOcrRepair` to use `i` instead of `l` as the default for mixed-case (since Fix 1's analysis conclusively shows `i` is correct far more often for recipe text), or (b) add a dedicated `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` variant that uses `i`. Option (a) is simpler and the fix is clear:\n\n```typescript\n// In applyBlindOcrRepair, change the fallback token call:\nreturn applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"i\"); // was \"l\"\n```\n\nThis also makes `generateBlindOcrVariants` cleaner since the `l`-variant would then become the non-default one.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `burstEnd` coordinate space mismatch in `isTitleAbsentPage`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:994-995`\n\n**Impact**: `isTitleAbsentPage` receives a wrong `startFrom` value in about half the cases where `burstEnd > 0`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `burstEnd` returned from `buildCandidates` is expressed as a **raw line index** in the original `lines` array (see line 730: `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0`). But `isTitleAbsentPage` calls `lines.slice(startFrom)`, where `lines` is the original `text.split(\"\\n\")` array. This is correct — both use the same coordinate space.\n\nHowever, `findBurstEnd` operates on `nonEmptyLines` (the filtered, compacted array with no blank lines), and `burstEnd` in `buildCandidates` local scope is an index into `nonEmptyLines`. The conversion `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0` translates this to a raw line index correctly.\n\nBut there is an edge case: when `burstEnd` exactly equals `nonEmptyLines.length` (burst consumed all non-empty lines), the expression `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index` evaluates to `undefined`, falling back to `0`. This means `isTitleAbsentPage` would be called with `startFrom = 0` — the exact opposite of the intent — and would evaluate the prologue lines that were just determined to be body content, potentially returning `true` and suppressing extraction of a title that exists after the burst.\n\nThis edge case is unlikely in practice (a file with zero non-burst non-empty lines would have no candidates anyway), but it's a semantic inversion of the fallback: `?? 0` should arguably be `?? lines.length` to express \"no lines remain to check.\"\n\n**Solution**:\n```typescript\n// In buildCandidates return statements, change the fallback:\nreturn { candidates, burstEnd: nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? lines.length };\n// And in the prioritized path:\nreturn { candidates: prioritized.slice(0, 25), burstEnd: nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? lines.length };\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 3. `isContinuation` predicate is subsumed by `isProse`, creating dead code and understated permissiveness\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:493`\n\n**Impact**: The unified prologue detector in `findBurstEnd` introduces three predicates: `isInstruction`, `isProse`, and `isContinuation`. Every line that satisfies `isContinuation` (lowercase start + `wordCount >= 2`) also satisfies `isProse` if it has 4+ words, because `isProse` includes `/^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/` as its first branch (with `wordCount >= 4`). However, `isContinuation` has a lower word-count threshold (2 words, not 4). So `isContinuation` extends `isProse` to 2–3 word lowercase-starting lines.\n\nThis is undocumented behavior. A 2-word lowercase line like `creamy texture.` will be counted as body content and extend the prologue skip. The improvement plan only discusses this case in the context of \"start lowercase or with a comma/conjunction\" but doesn't analyze the word-count=2 path explicitly. The plan describes this as equivalent to the old prose check, but the old check required 4+ words.\n\nThe net effect is the unified detector is more aggressive than documented. For the Mushroom Risotto case this is fine (all lines are 6+ words). But a recipe that legitimately opens with a 2-word title on line 0 followed by a 2-word instruction fragment would be at higher risk. The `i === 0` guard mitigates this — the skip only fires when no burst was detected — but it's worth naming explicitly.\n\n**Solution**: Either rename `isContinuation` to `isShortProse` and document the 2-word threshold explicitly, or raise its threshold to 4 words (matching `isProse`) and explain the rationale. The former is preferred:\n\n```typescript\n// Rename for clarity; keep threshold but document intent\nconst isShortLowercaseLine = /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) && wordCount(t) >= 2;\n// Note: lower threshold than isProse (2 vs 4 words) — catches short continuation fragments\n// like \"creamy texture.\" that follow cooking instructions. This adds permissiveness vs the\n// old separate checks; raise to 4 if regressions appear.\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. The cap on positional boost doesn't cover the direct-successor bonus for candidates at index 1 and 2\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1175-1185`\n\n**Impact**: The cap logic (lines 1175–1185) only tracks `totalPositionalBoost = firstCandidate.score - baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses`. The `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` is captured at line 1123, before both the first-after-preamble bonus AND the direct-successor bonus. But the direct-successor bonus loop (lines 1152–1173) also modifies candidates at `ci = 1` and `ci = 2`, and those modifications are never capped. So the comment at line 1176 (\"covers all of them\") is inaccurate — it only covers candidate index 0.\n\nFor `ci = 1` and `ci = 2`, the direct-successor bonus adds +0.10 uncapped. This is unlikely to cause problems in practice (the bonus is only +0.10 and the cap's purpose is mainly to prevent first-candidate domination), but the comment is misleading.\n\n**Solution**: Either extend the cap to apply to all three candidates, or update the comment to accurately describe what's capped:\n\n```typescript\n// Cap applies to the first candidate only (index 0). Candidates at index 1-2\n// receive the direct-successor bonus uncapped (+0.10 max since only one bonus fires for them).\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. Subset dedup food-category suffix protection uses `a.text.slice(b.text.length)` without case normalization\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1521-1525`\n\n**Impact**: The suffix extraction at line 1521 does `a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim()`. This works correctly when `b.text` is a case-exact prefix of `a.text`. However, `a.text` could be ALL_CAPS (`LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`) while `b.text` could be mixed-case (`Lemon Herb Roasted`) — they match via `aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase())` but the slice position is computed on the original case-sensitive strings. Since `b.text.length` is the same regardless of case, the slice is positionally correct but `a.text.slice(b.text.length)` gives ` VEGETABLES` (with leading space), which `.trim()` reduces to `VEGETABLES`. `stripDiacritics(\"VEGETABLES\".toLowerCase())` = `\"vegetables\"`, which is in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. So the logic actually works here.\n\nBut the `startsWith` guard at line 1520 (`aLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")`) correctly normalizes both sides. The subsequent slice on the original-case `a.text` is consistent with that guard's match position. This is fine.\n\nThe only real edge is a multi-word food category suffix like `\"owoce morza\"` (seafood) which would not be caught because `a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim()` would give `OWOCE MORZA` and `stripDiacritics(\"OWOCE MORZA\".toLowerCase())` = `\"owoce morza\"` — which IS in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. This case is handled correctly.\n\nThe logic is sound. The concern in the focus areas is not a real edge case. However, the `startsWith` constraint means this protection only fires when `b` is a true prefix. A join like `VEGETABLES LEMON HERB ROASTED` (suffix in a different position) would not be protected — but that's the correct behavior since it's not a \"category suffix.\"\n\nNo change required; this is a documentation/naming issue, not a bug.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `buildCandidates` return type change (`{ candidates, burstEnd }`) is minimal and clean. Both call sites (line 994 for candidates, line 995 for `isTitleAbsentPage`, and lines 1344/1547 for corroboration) use `burstEnd` correctly and consistently. The coordinate translation via `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index` is the right approach.\n\n- Extracting `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` as a parameterized helper and building both `applyBlindOcrRepair` and `generateBlindOcrVariants` on top of it is a genuine improvement in cohesion. The old `normalizeOcrTitle` had the token logic duplicated inline.\n\n- The `hasErraticCasing` threshold (`upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3`) is well-calibrated for its target case (`KoPyTka`: 3 inner-uppercase, 3 inner-lowercase → 3 >= 3×0.3 = 0.9). It correctly exempts words with a single mid-word capital like `McDonald` (1 inner uppercase, 6 lowercase → 1 < 6×0.3 = 1.8). The `word.length < 3` guard prevents false positives on 2-letter abbreviations.\n\n- The `normalizeErraticCasing` function correctly preserves whitespace tokens by splitting on `(\\s+)` with a capture group and filtering the spaces back in. This is a subtle correctness point that the old prose-prologue logic also handled correctly.\n\n- The overflow marker regex broadening (`PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\b` — removing the mandatory third word) is conservative and correct. The bracketed annotation check (`/^\\[.*\\b(PREVIOUS|CORRUPTED|...)\\b.*\\]$/i`) is safe because `^` and `$` guarantee it only fires on fully-bracketed lines, eliminating most false-positive risk.\n\n- The direct-successor blank-line scan is the minimal correct fix for its stated problem. Using `lines[prevPos]` (the raw original `lines` array) is correct here because `candidate.position` is a raw line index.\n\n## Proactive Suggestions\n\n- **The `applyBlindOcrRepair` mixed-case default should be `i`, not `l`.** The analysis in the improvement plan and the Fix 1 implementation both conclude that `i` is the correct default. Making it the actual default in `applyBlindOcrRepair` (not just in candidate generation) would make `normalizeOcrTitle`'s output consistent with what the embedding scorer selected. The `l`-variant would then be the explicit exception in `generateBlindOcrVariants`. This directly resolves the High Priority issue 1 above and simplifies the mental model of the whole repair subsystem.\n\n- **Consider naming the `i === 0` guard in `findBurstEnd` more explicitly.** The current comment says \"Skip body-content prologues\" but the guard condition `if (i === 0)` means this block only fires when overflow detection and garbled-burst detection both produced no skip. That three-way interaction is not documented in the comment. A brief note — \"Only applies when no overflow or garbled-burst was detected (i still 0 after those checks)\" — would help the next reviewer."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a40f02ac72bb823a1 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 60124\ntool_uses: 10\nduration_ms: 124495</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"66d6120a-7fee-4673-bb0a-75db3320d34d","uuid":"b97fb2d5-af99-4977-8c46-bb50e41bfc8c","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the architecture and design of the changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts.\n\n## Context\nThis is iteration 28 of a title extraction optimization loop for a React Native recipe photo app. The code extracts recipe titles from OCR text using heuristics + semantic embeddings. It runs on mobile (must complete under 10 seconds total).\n\n## The improvement plan is at tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md — read it for the planned fixes.\n\n## Changes (read the diff carefully)\nThe diff from HEAD~1 implements 4 fixes:\n1. **Dual-variant blind OCR repair** — generates both `1→i` and `1→l` variants instead of always choosing `l`. Adds `hasErraticCasing`/`normalizeErraticCasing` for cases like `KoPyTka`.\n2. **Direct-successor bonus skips blank lines** — scans backward past blank lines to find section headers.\n3. **Broadened overflow marker regex** — matches more natural corruption markers like `CORRUPTED TEXT` and `PARTIAL RECIPE`.\n4. **Unified body-content prologue detector** — replaces separate instruction/prose prologue checks with a unified one that handles interleaving.\n\nAlso:\n- `buildCandidates` now returns `{ candidates, burstEnd }` instead of just the array\n- `isTitleAbsentPage` accepts a `startFrom` parameter to skip burst lines\n- `passesCorroboration` accepts a `startLine` parameter\n- `normalizeOcrTitle` refactored to use shared `applyBlindOcrRepair`\n- Subset dedup logic enhanced to protect multi-line joins with food-category suffixes\n\n## Focus Areas\n1. Is the `buildCandidates` return type change clean? Does the burstEnd threading through the pipeline make sense?\n2. Does the unified prologue detector properly replace the two separate checks without regression risk?\n3. Is the erratic casing detection (`hasErraticCasing`) well-calibrated? Could it produce false positives?\n4. Does the subset dedup enhancement (food-category suffix protection) create any edge cases?\n5. Is the overall flow coherent — do the 4 fixes compose well without unintended interactions?\n\nRead the source file and the improvement plan, then provide your assessment.","agentId":"a40f02ac72bb823a1","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me provide the architectural review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Architecture & Design — Title Extractor Iteration 28\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1 (`lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`, ~1660 lines)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe four fixes are mechanically sound and accurately match the improvement plan's intent. The `buildCandidates` return type change threads cleanly through the pipeline. The main architectural tension is in Fix 4 (unified prologue detector): the new `isContinuation` predicate substantially overlaps with `isProse`, and the combination produces a more permissive gate than stated in the plan's risk section. There is also an unresolved inconsistency between where `applyBlindOcrRepair` is called in `normalizeOcrTitle` (always uses `l`-variant for mixed-case) versus the new dual-variant approach used during candidate generation (which correctly defers to the embedding scorer). This is a post-selection inconsistency, not a candidate-generation bug, but it means a title selected via the correct `i`-variant can be corrupted back to `l` on output.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 1. `normalizeOcrTitle` still uses `l`-variant for mixed-case output\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:958`\n\n**Impact**: Fix 1 correctly generates both `i` and `l` variants during candidate generation and lets the embedding scorer pick the better one. But `normalizeOcrTitle` at line 958 calls `applyBlindOcrRepair(text)`, which internally routes mixed-case text through `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"l\")` — the `l`-variant. If the embedding scorer selects the `i`-variant (`Braised Cod with White Wine`), that exact string reaches `normalizeOcrTitle`. The string no longer contains any `1` artifacts, so `applyBlindOcrRepair` is a no-op for it — this specific case is actually fine. But if the raw OCR text itself is what wins (the non-repaired form with `1` artifacts), `normalizeOcrTitle` will apply the wrong substitution.\n\nThe root issue is that `normalizeOcrTitle` is called on `s.text` at lines 1631 and 1636, and `s.text` is the candidate string that won scoring. If a raw-form candidate (`Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`) somehow wins over both variants (e.g., when candidate cap is hit and only the raw form is retained), `normalizeOcrTitle` will produce `Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `applyBlindOcrRepair` was refactored to be the single shared implementation (good), but it still hardcodes `l` for mixed-case. The `normalizeOcrTitle` path was not updated to use the `i`-variant logic.\n\n**Solution**: Either (a) change `applyBlindOcrRepair` to use `i` instead of `l` as the default for mixed-case (since Fix 1's analysis conclusively shows `i` is correct far more often for recipe text), or (b) add a dedicated `applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase` variant that uses `i`. Option (a) is simpler and the fix is clear:\n\n```typescript\n// In applyBlindOcrRepair, change the fallback token call:\nreturn applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"i\"); // was \"l\"\n```\n\nThis also makes `generateBlindOcrVariants` cleaner since the `l`-variant would then become the non-default one.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `burstEnd` coordinate space mismatch in `isTitleAbsentPage`\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:994-995`\n\n**Impact**: `isTitleAbsentPage` receives a wrong `startFrom` value in about half the cases where `burstEnd > 0`.\n\n**Root Cause**: `burstEnd` returned from `buildCandidates` is expressed as a **raw line index** in the original `lines` array (see line 730: `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0`). But `isTitleAbsentPage` calls `lines.slice(startFrom)`, where `lines` is the original `text.split(\"\\n\")` array. This is correct — both use the same coordinate space.\n\nHowever, `findBurstEnd` operates on `nonEmptyLines` (the filtered, compacted array with no blank lines), and `burstEnd` in `buildCandidates` local scope is an index into `nonEmptyLines`. The conversion `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0` translates this to a raw line index correctly.\n\nBut there is an edge case: when `burstEnd` exactly equals `nonEmptyLines.length` (burst consumed all non-empty lines), the expression `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index` evaluates to `undefined`, falling back to `0`. This means `isTitleAbsentPage` would be called with `startFrom = 0` — the exact opposite of the intent — and would evaluate the prologue lines that were just determined to be body content, potentially returning `true` and suppressing extraction of a title that exists after the burst.\n\nThis edge case is unlikely in practice (a file with zero non-burst non-empty lines would have no candidates anyway), but it's a semantic inversion of the fallback: `?? 0` should arguably be `?? lines.length` to express \"no lines remain to check.\"\n\n**Solution**:\n```typescript\n// In buildCandidates return statements, change the fallback:\nreturn { candidates, burstEnd: nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? lines.length };\n// And in the prioritized path:\nreturn { candidates: prioritized.slice(0, 25), burstEnd: nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? lines.length };\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 3. `isContinuation` predicate is subsumed by `isProse`, creating dead code and understated permissiveness\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:493`\n\n**Impact**: The unified prologue detector in `findBurstEnd` introduces three predicates: `isInstruction`, `isProse`, and `isContinuation`. Every line that satisfies `isContinuation` (lowercase start + `wordCount >= 2`) also satisfies `isProse` if it has 4+ words, because `isProse` includes `/^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/` as its first branch (with `wordCount >= 4`). However, `isContinuation` has a lower word-count threshold (2 words, not 4). So `isContinuation` extends `isProse` to 2–3 word lowercase-starting lines.\n\nThis is undocumented behavior. A 2-word lowercase line like `creamy texture.` will be counted as body content and extend the prologue skip. The improvement plan only discusses this case in the context of \"start lowercase or with a comma/conjunction\" but doesn't analyze the word-count=2 path explicitly. The plan describes this as equivalent to the old prose check, but the old check required 4+ words.\n\nThe net effect is the unified detector is more aggressive than documented. For the Mushroom Risotto case this is fine (all lines are 6+ words). But a recipe that legitimately opens with a 2-word title on line 0 followed by a 2-word instruction fragment would be at higher risk. The `i === 0` guard mitigates this — the skip only fires when no burst was detected — but it's worth naming explicitly.\n\n**Solution**: Either rename `isContinuation` to `isShortProse` and document the 2-word threshold explicitly, or raise its threshold to 4 words (matching `isProse`) and explain the rationale. The former is preferred:\n\n```typescript\n// Rename for clarity; keep threshold but document intent\nconst isShortLowercaseLine = /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) && wordCount(t) >= 2;\n// Note: lower threshold than isProse (2 vs 4 words) — catches short continuation fragments\n// like \"creamy texture.\" that follow cooking instructions. This adds permissiveness vs the\n// old separate checks; raise to 4 if regressions appear.\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. The cap on positional boost doesn't cover the direct-successor bonus for candidates at index 1 and 2\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1175-1185`\n\n**Impact**: The cap logic (lines 1175–1185) only tracks `totalPositionalBoost = firstCandidate.score - baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses`. The `baseScoreBeforePositionalBonuses` is captured at line 1123, before both the first-after-preamble bonus AND the direct-successor bonus. But the direct-successor bonus loop (lines 1152–1173) also modifies candidates at `ci = 1` and `ci = 2`, and those modifications are never capped. So the comment at line 1176 (\"covers all of them\") is inaccurate — it only covers candidate index 0.\n\nFor `ci = 1` and `ci = 2`, the direct-successor bonus adds +0.10 uncapped. This is unlikely to cause problems in practice (the bonus is only +0.10 and the cap's purpose is mainly to prevent first-candidate domination), but the comment is misleading.\n\n**Solution**: Either extend the cap to apply to all three candidates, or update the comment to accurately describe what's capped:\n\n```typescript\n// Cap applies to the first candidate only (index 0). Candidates at index 1-2\n// receive the direct-successor bonus uncapped (+0.10 max since only one bonus fires for them).\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. Subset dedup food-category suffix protection uses `a.text.slice(b.text.length)` without case normalization\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1521-1525`\n\n**Impact**: The suffix extraction at line 1521 does `a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim()`. This works correctly when `b.text` is a case-exact prefix of `a.text`. However, `a.text` could be ALL_CAPS (`LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES`) while `b.text` could be mixed-case (`Lemon Herb Roasted`) — they match via `aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase())` but the slice position is computed on the original case-sensitive strings. Since `b.text.length` is the same regardless of case, the slice is positionally correct but `a.text.slice(b.text.length)` gives ` VEGETABLES` (with leading space), which `.trim()` reduces to `VEGETABLES`. `stripDiacritics(\"VEGETABLES\".toLowerCase())` = `\"vegetables\"`, which is in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. So the logic actually works here.\n\nBut the `startsWith` guard at line 1520 (`aLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")`) correctly normalizes both sides. The subsequent slice on the original-case `a.text` is consistent with that guard's match position. This is fine.\n\nThe only real edge is a multi-word food category suffix like `\"owoce morza\"` (seafood) which would not be caught because `a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim()` would give `OWOCE MORZA` and `stripDiacritics(\"OWOCE MORZA\".toLowerCase())` = `\"owoce morza\"` — which IS in `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS`. This case is handled correctly.\n\nThe logic is sound. The concern in the focus areas is not a real edge case. However, the `startsWith` constraint means this protection only fires when `b` is a true prefix. A join like `VEGETABLES LEMON HERB ROASTED` (suffix in a different position) would not be protected — but that's the correct behavior since it's not a \"category suffix.\"\n\nNo change required; this is a documentation/naming issue, not a bug.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The `buildCandidates` return type change (`{ candidates, burstEnd }`) is minimal and clean. Both call sites (line 994 for candidates, line 995 for `isTitleAbsentPage`, and lines 1344/1547 for corroboration) use `burstEnd` correctly and consistently. The coordinate translation via `nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index` is the right approach.\n\n- Extracting `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` as a parameterized helper and building both `applyBlindOcrRepair` and `generateBlindOcrVariants` on top of it is a genuine improvement in cohesion. The old `normalizeOcrTitle` had the token logic duplicated inline.\n\n- The `hasErraticCasing` threshold (`upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3`) is well-calibrated for its target case (`KoPyTka`: 3 inner-uppercase, 3 inner-lowercase → 3 >= 3×0.3 = 0.9). It correctly exempts words with a single mid-word capital like `McDonald` (1 inner uppercase, 6 lowercase → 1 < 6×0.3 = 1.8). The `word.length < 3` guard prevents false positives on 2-letter abbreviations.\n\n- The `normalizeErraticCasing` function correctly preserves whitespace tokens by splitting on `(\\s+)` with a capture group and filtering the spaces back in. This is a subtle correctness point that the old prose-prologue logic also handled correctly.\n\n- The overflow marker regex broadening (`PREVIOUS\\s+(RECIPE|PAGE)\\b` — removing the mandatory third word) is conservative and correct. The bracketed annotation check (`/^\\[.*\\b(PREVIOUS|CORRUPTED|...)\\b.*\\]$/i`) is safe because `^` and `$` guarantee it only fires on fully-bracketed lines, eliminating most false-positive risk.\n\n- The direct-successor blank-line scan is the minimal correct fix for its stated problem. Using `lines[prevPos]` (the raw original `lines` array) is correct here because `candidate.position` is a raw line index.\n\n## Proactive Suggestions\n\n- **The `applyBlindOcrRepair` mixed-case default should be `i`, not `l`.** The analysis in the improvement plan and the Fix 1 implementation both conclude that `i` is the correct default. Making it the actual default in `applyBlindOcrRepair` (not just in candidate generation) would make `normalizeOcrTitle`'s output consistent with what the embedding scorer selected. The `l`-variant would then be the explicit exception in `generateBlindOcrVariants`. This directly resolves the High Priority issue 1 above and simplifies the mental model of the whole repair subsystem.\n\n- **Consider naming the `i === 0` guard in `findBurstEnd` more explicitly.** The current comment says \"Skip body-content prologues\" but the guard condition `if (i === 0)` means this block only fires when overflow detection and garbled-burst detection both produced no skip. That three-way interaction is not documented in the comment. A brief note — \"Only applies when no overflow or garbled-burst was detected (i still 0 after those checks)\" — would help the next reviewer."}],"totalDurationMs":124495,"totalTokens":60124,"totalToolUseCount":10,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5973,"cache_read_input_tokens":50313,"output_tokens":3837,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5973},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
