{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DWZvkYLSgR3KWoyc1JyPBq","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts (HEAD~1 to HEAD + unstaged)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1 (1661 lines, ~200 lines changed)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 4\n- Low Priority / Suggestions: 4\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe four fixes are well-motivated and the refactoring of OCR repair logic into named functions is a clear improvement over the previous inline block. The most significant concerns are a subtle dominance bug in `isContinuation` that swallows `isProse`'s word-count guard, and a readability problem in the subset dedup enhancement where the condition structure obscures intent.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `isContinuation` makes `isProse` dead in the common case\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:487-495`\n\nThe three conditions are evaluated in order, and `isContinuation` at line 493 is strictly broader than `isProse` at line 488:\n\n```\nisProse:        (lowercaseStart OR ends-comma OR (ends-period AND >4 words)) AND wordCount >= 4\nisContinuation: lowercaseStart AND wordCount >= 2\n```\n\nAny lowercase-starting line with 4+ words that matches `isProse` also matches `isContinuation`. The only case `isProse` catches that `isContinuation` does not is `ends-comma` and `ends-period` patterns that start with an uppercase letter — but such lines would not be caught by the old `isBodyText` check either. The practical effect is that the word-count guard (`>= 4`) in `isProse` is never the deciding factor; `isContinuation`'s threshold of `>= 2` always fires first.\n\nThis is probably not causing test failures now because `isContinuation` being looser errs on the side of skipping more preamble lines, but it does mean `isProse`'s carefully-tuned body-text definition is dead code in this path.\n\nThe original two-pass design had `isBodyText` (effectively `isProse`) as a single combined check. The refactoring into three separate variables makes the overlap invisible. Consider whether `isContinuation` was intended to replace `isProse` entirely or to be a complementary weaker check:\n\n```typescript\n// Option A: Drop isProse from findBurstEnd — isContinuation fully subsumes it\nconst isContinuation = /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) && wordCount(t) >= 2;\nif (isInstruction || isContinuation) {\n\n// Option B: Remove isContinuation and restore the original intent\n// isProse handles lowercase-start lines with >= 4 words\n// isInstruction handles imperative-verb sentences regardless of case\nif (isInstruction || isProse) {\n```\n\nThe `isBodyProse` function (used in `isTitleAbsentPage` at line 381) uses `wordCount >= 4` as its threshold. It's worth deciding whether the threshold in `findBurstEnd` should match it, and documenting why it differs if intentionally looser.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `buildCandidates` blind OCR block mutates `repairable` and then discards the normalized form for variant generation\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:657-683`\n\nThe block introduces a mutable `repairable` variable that starts as `singleText`, optionally updates to the casing-normalized form, then passes `repairable` to `generateBlindOcrVariants`. This is correct behavior, but the implementation has a subtle issue: if `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` is true but the normalized form fails `passesHardFilters`, `repairable` is still assigned the normalized text (line 665-666 show the `passesHardFilters` check gates the `candidates.push` but not the assignment). Subsequent `generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable)` then generates variants from the normalized text even when the normalized text itself was rejected, which may produce variants the scorer never needed. This is harmless in practice (variants still pass their own `passesHardFilters` check) but the code reads as if the assignment is conditional when it isn't.\n\n```typescript\n// Current — repairable is always updated even when the normalised form is rejected\nlet repairable = singleText;\nif (hasErraticCasing(repairable)) {\n  repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);   // unconditional assignment\n  if (repairable !== singleText && passesHardFilters(repairable)) {\n    // push...\n  }\n}\n\n// Clearer intent — assign only when the normalized form is usable\nlet repairable = singleText;\nconst caseNormalized = hasErraticCasing(repairable) ? normalizeErraticCasing(repairable) : repairable;\nif (caseNormalized !== repairable && passesHardFilters(caseNormalized)) {\n  const norm = caseNormalized.toLowerCase();\n  if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n    seen.add(norm);\n    candidates.push({ text: caseNormalized, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n  }\n  repairable = caseNormalized;\n}\nconst variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable);\n```\n\nThis makes it explicit that `repairable` is only promoted to the casing-normalized form when that form is valid.\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### 3. `hasErraticCasing` threshold `0.3` is unexplained\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:892`\n\n```typescript\nreturn upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3;\n```\n\nThe `0.3` ratio is a magic number. A reader cannot tell whether this means \"at least 30% of inner letters are uppercase\" or what edge case it guards against. Given that `upperInner >= 2` is also required, the ratio fires in many cases (a 10-letter word with 3 uppercase inner letters passes). A comment explaining the calibration would help:\n\n```typescript\n// Ratio guards against words like \"McCarthy\" (1 upper inner out of 6 lower = 17%)\n// while catching \"KoPyTka\" (3 upper inner, 2 lower = 150%) and \"KUrczAK\" (3:2 = 150%).\n// 0.3 means: erratic if upper count ≥ 30% of lower count.\nreturn upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3;\n```\n\nSimilarly, the `corroboratedCount` thresholds in `passesCorroboration` at line 267 (`1.0` and `0.67`) lack inline calibration notes.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Subset dedup enhancement — readability of the protection guard\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1519-1526`\n\nThe new guard is functionally correct but takes multiple reads to parse because the predicate inside `!selected.some(...)` returns `false` to mean \"don't remove `a`\":\n\n```typescript\nif ((a.origin === \"2-line\" || a.origin === \"3-line\") &&\n    aLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")) {\n  const suffix = a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim();\n  const suffixNorm = stripDiacritics(suffix.toLowerCase());\n  if (CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(suffixNorm)) {\n    return false; // Don't remove `a` — its suffix is a food-category label\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe `return false` here means \"b does NOT cause a to be removed\", which is the double-negative path inside an outer `!selected.some(...)`. The comment helps but the structure is still non-obvious. An early-return/extraction would separate concerns:\n\n```typescript\n// Before the main dedup filter — extract as a guard function\nfunction isProtectedFromDedup(\n  a: { text: string; origin: CandidateOrigin },\n  b: { text: string }\n): boolean {\n  if (a.origin !== \"2-line\" && a.origin !== \"3-line\") return false;\n  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n  const bLower = b.text.toLowerCase();\n  if (!aLower.startsWith(bLower + \" \")) return false;\n  const suffix = a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim();\n  return CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(stripDiacritics(suffix.toLowerCase()));\n}\n```\n\nThis makes the dedup predicate itself flat:\n\n```typescript\nreturn !selected.some((b) => {\n  if (b === a) return false;\n  if (b.text.length >= a.text.length) return false;\n  if (!aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase())) return false;\n  if (isProtectedFromDedup(a, b)) return false;\n  return true;\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `normalizeErraticCasing` calls `hasErraticCasing` per-token, which re-scans the whole token word-by-word\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:896-905`\n\n`normalizeErraticCasing` splits on whitespace-runs, then for each non-space token calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` (line 900), which internally calls `text.split(/\\s+/)` again on a single token (redundant, but not wrong) and then matches two regex patterns. For single-word tokens there is no observable cost, but the design suggests `hasErraticCasing` was conceived as a word-level function while its signature takes full text. Consider a `_word` variant or a direct inline check to avoid the conceptual mismatch:\n\n```typescript\n// Direct inline — eliminates the hasErraticCasing(singleToken) double-split\nfunction normalizeErraticCasing(text: string): string {\n  return text.split(/(\\s+)/).map(token => {\n    if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n    if (isAllCaps(token)) return token;\n    const inner = token.slice(1);\n    const upperInner = (inner.match(/[A-ZÀ-Ż]/g) || []).length;\n    const lowerInner = (inner.match(/[a-zà-ż]/g) || []).length;\n    if (token.length >= 3 && upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3) {\n      return token.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + token.slice(1).toLowerCase();\n    }\n    return token;\n  }).join(\"\");\n}\n```\n\nThe downside is that the threshold `0.3` would now appear in two places instead of one — which is an argument for naming the constant.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` has a character-range asymmetry between ALL_CAPS and mixed-case branches\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:845-857`\n\nThe ALL_CAPS branch uses `[A-Z]` lookahead/lookbehind (ASCII only), while `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s ALL_CAPS branch (line 865-876) uses `[A-ZÀ-Ż]` to cover Polish capital diacritics. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` is only reached from the mixed-case path in `applyBlindOcrRepair` (it handles ALL_CAPS tokens within mixed-case strings), so the narrower range means Polish all-caps words like \"ŻUREK\" or \"ŁOSOŚ\" embedded in a mixed-case title won't have their `0` repaired to `O`. Whether this matters in practice depends on the input set, but the inconsistency is a latent bug. The ALL_CAPS branch in `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` should match the range used in `applyBlindOcrRepair`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token: string, oneLetter: \"i\" | \"l\"): string {\n  if (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n    return token\n      .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n      .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")   // was [A-Z]\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\");  // was [A-Z]\n  }\n  // ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## Low Priority / Suggestions\n\n### 7. `generateBlindOcrVariants` duplicates the split-map-join pattern\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:921-925`\n\nThe `iVariant` generation in `generateBlindOcrVariants` replicates the exact split-map-join structure already in `applyBlindOcrRepair`, just with `\"i\"` instead of `\"l\"`. A symmetric call would remove the duplication:\n\n```typescript\nconst iVariant = text.split(/(\\s+)/).map((token) => {\n  if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n  return applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"i\");\n}).join(\"\");\n\n// Could be:\nconst applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase = (text: string, oneLetter: \"i\" | \"l\") =>\n  text.split(/(\\s+)/).map((token) => /^\\s+$/.test(token) ? token : applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, oneLetter)).join(\"\");\n\nconst iVariant = applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase(text, \"i\");\nconst lVariant = applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase(text, \"l\");\n```\n\n`applyBlindOcrRepair` itself could then delegate to this helper, eliminating the last duplication.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Comments in the blind OCR block explain \"what\" adequately; \"why line.index <= 5\" is not stated\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:662`\n\nThe comment block at lines 657-661 explains the overall purpose well. The constant `5` (line 662) is the only thing that lacks a rationale:\n\n```typescript\n// Limit to the first 6 source lines (index 0-5): beyond this, positional evidence\n// is too weak to justify speculative blind repair — the embedding score alone must\n// distinguish the title.\nif (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n```\n\n---\n\n### 9. `burstEnd` naming in the return value\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:727-730`\n\n`buildCandidates` now returns `burstEnd: nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0`. The variable inside the function (`burstEnd`) is an index into `nonEmptyLines`, but the returned value is the source-line index (`nonEmptyLines[burstEnd].index`), i.e., an index into a different coordinate space. The transformation is correct and the callers use it correctly (`passesCorroboration(cap.text, cap.position, lines, burstEnd)` where `lines` is the raw array), but the naming of the return field `burstEnd` is ambiguous — it could be either. A name like `burstEndLineIndex` for the returned field (and keeping the internal variable as-is) would avoid confusion when reading call sites.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The extraction of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` removes a genuine copy-paste risk: the old `normalizeOcrTitle` had the per-token logic inline and it diverged from `applyBlindOcrRepair` in one detail (the old mixed-case branch hardcoded `\"l\"`, the new one uses the parameter). The refactoring makes that explicit and testable.\n- The `burstEnd` plumbing through `buildCandidates` into `isTitleAbsentPage` and `passesCorroboration` is the right architectural move — passing it as a parameter instead of recomputing it avoids subtle inconsistencies where the two calls might have disagreed on what \"start\" means.\n- The `findBurstEnd` consolidation (merge of the instruction-skip and prose-skip loops) is a genuine simplification, reducing two while-loops to one.\n- Comment quality on the OCR functions is good — the JSDoc on `applyBlindOcrRepair` and `generateBlindOcrVariants` explains the \"why\" (positional evidence, ambiguity between `i` and `l`) not just the \"what\".\n- The `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` set and the `isCategorySectionLabel` helper are well-named and correctly separated from `SECTION_LABELS`, making the dedup exception readable at the data-structure level even when the predicate around it is dense.\n\n## Systemic Patterns\n\nTwo patterns recur across this file and are worth a team-level note:\n\n1. **Magic ratio constants without names.** `0.3`, `0.67`, `0.15`, `0.12`, `0.08`, `0.10` all appear as bare floats. In isolation each is defensible, but collectively they make re-calibration opaque. A small `SCORING_CONSTANTS` object or named consts at the top of the scoring section would make tuning iterations faster and make the improvement-plan's \"what changed\" obvious in diffs.\n\n2. **The dedup filter at line 1506 contains a `DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC` warning**, which indicates this section has been broken by well-intentioned edits repeatedly. The new `isProtectedFromDedup` extraction (suggested above) would help, but the deeper issue is that the dedup semantics (\"shorter wins unless protected\") are entangled with the candidate-pre-filtering logic in the 200 lines before it. A single integration test that covers the `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` case end-to-end (not just the dedup step) would make the invariant verifiable and reduce the need for the warning."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ad77bff6386d227a1 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 59001\ntool_uses: 19\nduration_ms: 138285</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"66d6120a-7fee-4673-bb0a-75db3320d34d","uuid":"69ecbd5e-25c5-413f-a8a3-90d555c92d44","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review code quality and maintainability of the changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts.\n\n## Context\nThis is a recipe title extractor for a React Native app. The diff (HEAD~1 to HEAD, plus unstaged changes) implements 4 fixes from an improvement plan.\n\nRead the full file at lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts and focus on:\n\n1. **Naming quality** — Are `applyBlindOcrRepairToken`, `generateBlindOcrVariants`, `hasErraticCasing`, `normalizeErraticCasing` clear and descriptive?\n2. **Code duplication** — The old `normalizeOcrTitle` had inline OCR repair logic that's now extracted to `applyBlindOcrRepair`. Is the refactoring clean? Any remaining duplication?\n3. **Function complexity** — `buildCandidates` is already long. Does the new blind OCR repair block (lines ~657-688) add too much inline complexity? Should it be extracted?\n4. **Comment quality** — Are the new comments helpful or noise? Do they explain \"why\" not just \"what\"?\n5. **Magic numbers** — Check for unexplained constants (thresholds, regex patterns).\n6. **The subset dedup enhancement** (around line 1507-1530) — is the logic readable? The nested conditions with `startsWith` and `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` check.\n7. **Dead code or unused paths** — Did the refactoring leave anything orphaned?\n\nProvide specific line references and suggestions.","agentId":"ad77bff6386d227a1","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts (HEAD~1 to HEAD + unstaged)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 1 (1661 lines, ~200 lines changed)\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 2\n- Medium Priority: 4\n- Low Priority / Suggestions: 4\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe four fixes are well-motivated and the refactoring of OCR repair logic into named functions is a clear improvement over the previous inline block. The most significant concerns are a subtle dominance bug in `isContinuation` that swallows `isProse`'s word-count guard, and a readability problem in the subset dedup enhancement where the condition structure obscures intent.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `isContinuation` makes `isProse` dead in the common case\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:487-495`\n\nThe three conditions are evaluated in order, and `isContinuation` at line 493 is strictly broader than `isProse` at line 488:\n\n```\nisProse:        (lowercaseStart OR ends-comma OR (ends-period AND >4 words)) AND wordCount >= 4\nisContinuation: lowercaseStart AND wordCount >= 2\n```\n\nAny lowercase-starting line with 4+ words that matches `isProse` also matches `isContinuation`. The only case `isProse` catches that `isContinuation` does not is `ends-comma` and `ends-period` patterns that start with an uppercase letter — but such lines would not be caught by the old `isBodyText` check either. The practical effect is that the word-count guard (`>= 4`) in `isProse` is never the deciding factor; `isContinuation`'s threshold of `>= 2` always fires first.\n\nThis is probably not causing test failures now because `isContinuation` being looser errs on the side of skipping more preamble lines, but it does mean `isProse`'s carefully-tuned body-text definition is dead code in this path.\n\nThe original two-pass design had `isBodyText` (effectively `isProse`) as a single combined check. The refactoring into three separate variables makes the overlap invisible. Consider whether `isContinuation` was intended to replace `isProse` entirely or to be a complementary weaker check:\n\n```typescript\n// Option A: Drop isProse from findBurstEnd — isContinuation fully subsumes it\nconst isContinuation = /^[a-ząćęłńóśźż]/.test(t) && wordCount(t) >= 2;\nif (isInstruction || isContinuation) {\n\n// Option B: Remove isContinuation and restore the original intent\n// isProse handles lowercase-start lines with >= 4 words\n// isInstruction handles imperative-verb sentences regardless of case\nif (isInstruction || isProse) {\n```\n\nThe `isBodyProse` function (used in `isTitleAbsentPage` at line 381) uses `wordCount >= 4` as its threshold. It's worth deciding whether the threshold in `findBurstEnd` should match it, and documenting why it differs if intentionally looser.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `buildCandidates` blind OCR block mutates `repairable` and then discards the normalized form for variant generation\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:657-683`\n\nThe block introduces a mutable `repairable` variable that starts as `singleText`, optionally updates to the casing-normalized form, then passes `repairable` to `generateBlindOcrVariants`. This is correct behavior, but the implementation has a subtle issue: if `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` is true but the normalized form fails `passesHardFilters`, `repairable` is still assigned the normalized text (line 665-666 show the `passesHardFilters` check gates the `candidates.push` but not the assignment). Subsequent `generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable)` then generates variants from the normalized text even when the normalized text itself was rejected, which may produce variants the scorer never needed. This is harmless in practice (variants still pass their own `passesHardFilters` check) but the code reads as if the assignment is conditional when it isn't.\n\n```typescript\n// Current — repairable is always updated even when the normalised form is rejected\nlet repairable = singleText;\nif (hasErraticCasing(repairable)) {\n  repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);   // unconditional assignment\n  if (repairable !== singleText && passesHardFilters(repairable)) {\n    // push...\n  }\n}\n\n// Clearer intent — assign only when the normalized form is usable\nlet repairable = singleText;\nconst caseNormalized = hasErraticCasing(repairable) ? normalizeErraticCasing(repairable) : repairable;\nif (caseNormalized !== repairable && passesHardFilters(caseNormalized)) {\n  const norm = caseNormalized.toLowerCase();\n  if (!seen.has(norm)) {\n    seen.add(norm);\n    candidates.push({ text: caseNormalized, position: line.index, origin: \"single\" });\n  }\n  repairable = caseNormalized;\n}\nconst variants = generateBlindOcrVariants(repairable);\n```\n\nThis makes it explicit that `repairable` is only promoted to the casing-normalized form when that form is valid.\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority\n\n### 3. `hasErraticCasing` threshold `0.3` is unexplained\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:892`\n\n```typescript\nreturn upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3;\n```\n\nThe `0.3` ratio is a magic number. A reader cannot tell whether this means \"at least 30% of inner letters are uppercase\" or what edge case it guards against. Given that `upperInner >= 2` is also required, the ratio fires in many cases (a 10-letter word with 3 uppercase inner letters passes). A comment explaining the calibration would help:\n\n```typescript\n// Ratio guards against words like \"McCarthy\" (1 upper inner out of 6 lower = 17%)\n// while catching \"KoPyTka\" (3 upper inner, 2 lower = 150%) and \"KUrczAK\" (3:2 = 150%).\n// 0.3 means: erratic if upper count ≥ 30% of lower count.\nreturn upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3;\n```\n\nSimilarly, the `corroboratedCount` thresholds in `passesCorroboration` at line 267 (`1.0` and `0.67`) lack inline calibration notes.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Subset dedup enhancement — readability of the protection guard\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:1519-1526`\n\nThe new guard is functionally correct but takes multiple reads to parse because the predicate inside `!selected.some(...)` returns `false` to mean \"don't remove `a`\":\n\n```typescript\nif ((a.origin === \"2-line\" || a.origin === \"3-line\") &&\n    aLower.startsWith(b.text.toLowerCase() + \" \")) {\n  const suffix = a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim();\n  const suffixNorm = stripDiacritics(suffix.toLowerCase());\n  if (CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(suffixNorm)) {\n    return false; // Don't remove `a` — its suffix is a food-category label\n  }\n}\n```\n\nThe `return false` here means \"b does NOT cause a to be removed\", which is the double-negative path inside an outer `!selected.some(...)`. The comment helps but the structure is still non-obvious. An early-return/extraction would separate concerns:\n\n```typescript\n// Before the main dedup filter — extract as a guard function\nfunction isProtectedFromDedup(\n  a: { text: string; origin: CandidateOrigin },\n  b: { text: string }\n): boolean {\n  if (a.origin !== \"2-line\" && a.origin !== \"3-line\") return false;\n  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n  const bLower = b.text.toLowerCase();\n  if (!aLower.startsWith(bLower + \" \")) return false;\n  const suffix = a.text.slice(b.text.length).trim();\n  return CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS.has(stripDiacritics(suffix.toLowerCase()));\n}\n```\n\nThis makes the dedup predicate itself flat:\n\n```typescript\nreturn !selected.some((b) => {\n  if (b === a) return false;\n  if (b.text.length >= a.text.length) return false;\n  if (!aLower.includes(b.text.toLowerCase())) return false;\n  if (isProtectedFromDedup(a, b)) return false;\n  return true;\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `normalizeErraticCasing` calls `hasErraticCasing` per-token, which re-scans the whole token word-by-word\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:896-905`\n\n`normalizeErraticCasing` splits on whitespace-runs, then for each non-space token calls `hasErraticCasing(token)` (line 900), which internally calls `text.split(/\\s+/)` again on a single token (redundant, but not wrong) and then matches two regex patterns. For single-word tokens there is no observable cost, but the design suggests `hasErraticCasing` was conceived as a word-level function while its signature takes full text. Consider a `_word` variant or a direct inline check to avoid the conceptual mismatch:\n\n```typescript\n// Direct inline — eliminates the hasErraticCasing(singleToken) double-split\nfunction normalizeErraticCasing(text: string): string {\n  return text.split(/(\\s+)/).map(token => {\n    if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n    if (isAllCaps(token)) return token;\n    const inner = token.slice(1);\n    const upperInner = (inner.match(/[A-ZÀ-Ż]/g) || []).length;\n    const lowerInner = (inner.match(/[a-zà-ż]/g) || []).length;\n    if (token.length >= 3 && upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3) {\n      return token.charAt(0).toUpperCase() + token.slice(1).toLowerCase();\n    }\n    return token;\n  }).join(\"\");\n}\n```\n\nThe downside is that the threshold `0.3` would now appear in two places instead of one — which is an argument for naming the constant.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` has a character-range asymmetry between ALL_CAPS and mixed-case branches\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:845-857`\n\nThe ALL_CAPS branch uses `[A-Z]` lookahead/lookbehind (ASCII only), while `applyBlindOcrRepair`'s ALL_CAPS branch (line 865-876) uses `[A-ZÀ-Ż]` to cover Polish capital diacritics. `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` is only reached from the mixed-case path in `applyBlindOcrRepair` (it handles ALL_CAPS tokens within mixed-case strings), so the narrower range means Polish all-caps words like \"ŻUREK\" or \"ŁOSOŚ\" embedded in a mixed-case title won't have their `0` repaired to `O`. Whether this matters in practice depends on the input set, but the inconsistency is a latent bug. The ALL_CAPS branch in `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` should match the range used in `applyBlindOcrRepair`:\n\n```typescript\nfunction applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token: string, oneLetter: \"i\" | \"l\"): string {\n  if (isAllCaps(token) && token.length > 1) {\n    return token\n      .replace(/1/g, \"I\")\n      .replace(/0(?=[A-ZÀ-Ż])/g, \"O\")   // was [A-Z]\n      .replace(/(?<=[A-ZÀ-Ż])0/g, \"O\");  // was [A-Z]\n  }\n  // ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## Low Priority / Suggestions\n\n### 7. `generateBlindOcrVariants` duplicates the split-map-join pattern\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:921-925`\n\nThe `iVariant` generation in `generateBlindOcrVariants` replicates the exact split-map-join structure already in `applyBlindOcrRepair`, just with `\"i\"` instead of `\"l\"`. A symmetric call would remove the duplication:\n\n```typescript\nconst iVariant = text.split(/(\\s+)/).map((token) => {\n  if (/^\\s+$/.test(token)) return token;\n  return applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"i\");\n}).join(\"\");\n\n// Could be:\nconst applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase = (text: string, oneLetter: \"i\" | \"l\") =>\n  text.split(/(\\s+)/).map((token) => /^\\s+$/.test(token) ? token : applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, oneLetter)).join(\"\");\n\nconst iVariant = applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase(text, \"i\");\nconst lVariant = applyBlindOcrRepairMixedCase(text, \"l\");\n```\n\n`applyBlindOcrRepair` itself could then delegate to this helper, eliminating the last duplication.\n\n---\n\n### 8. Comments in the blind OCR block explain \"what\" adequately; \"why line.index <= 5\" is not stated\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:662`\n\nThe comment block at lines 657-661 explains the overall purpose well. The constant `5` (line 662) is the only thing that lacks a rationale:\n\n```typescript\n// Limit to the first 6 source lines (index 0-5): beyond this, positional evidence\n// is too weak to justify speculative blind repair — the embedding score alone must\n// distinguish the title.\nif (line.index <= 5 && (OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text) || hasErraticCasing(line.text))) {\n```\n\n---\n\n### 9. `burstEnd` naming in the return value\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:727-730`\n\n`buildCandidates` now returns `burstEnd: nonEmptyLines[burstEnd]?.index ?? 0`. The variable inside the function (`burstEnd`) is an index into `nonEmptyLines`, but the returned value is the source-line index (`nonEmptyLines[burstEnd].index`), i.e., an index into a different coordinate space. The transformation is correct and the callers use it correctly (`passesCorroboration(cap.text, cap.position, lines, burstEnd)` where `lines` is the raw array), but the naming of the return field `burstEnd` is ambiguous — it could be either. A name like `burstEndLineIndex` for the returned field (and keeping the internal variable as-is) would avoid confusion when reading call sites.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The extraction of `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` removes a genuine copy-paste risk: the old `normalizeOcrTitle` had the per-token logic inline and it diverged from `applyBlindOcrRepair` in one detail (the old mixed-case branch hardcoded `\"l\"`, the new one uses the parameter). The refactoring makes that explicit and testable.\n- The `burstEnd` plumbing through `buildCandidates` into `isTitleAbsentPage` and `passesCorroboration` is the right architectural move — passing it as a parameter instead of recomputing it avoids subtle inconsistencies where the two calls might have disagreed on what \"start\" means.\n- The `findBurstEnd` consolidation (merge of the instruction-skip and prose-skip loops) is a genuine simplification, reducing two while-loops to one.\n- Comment quality on the OCR functions is good — the JSDoc on `applyBlindOcrRepair` and `generateBlindOcrVariants` explains the \"why\" (positional evidence, ambiguity between `i` and `l`) not just the \"what\".\n- The `CATEGORY_SECTION_LABELS` set and the `isCategorySectionLabel` helper are well-named and correctly separated from `SECTION_LABELS`, making the dedup exception readable at the data-structure level even when the predicate around it is dense.\n\n## Systemic Patterns\n\nTwo patterns recur across this file and are worth a team-level note:\n\n1. **Magic ratio constants without names.** `0.3`, `0.67`, `0.15`, `0.12`, `0.08`, `0.10` all appear as bare floats. In isolation each is defensible, but collectively they make re-calibration opaque. A small `SCORING_CONSTANTS` object or named consts at the top of the scoring section would make tuning iterations faster and make the improvement-plan's \"what changed\" obvious in diffs.\n\n2. **The dedup filter at line 1506 contains a `DO NOT CHANGE THIS LOGIC` warning**, which indicates this section has been broken by well-intentioned edits repeatedly. The new `isProtectedFromDedup` extraction (suggested above) would help, but the deeper issue is that the dedup semantics (\"shorter wins unless protected\") are entangled with the candidate-pre-filtering logic in the 200 lines before it. A single integration test that covers the `LEMON HERB ROASTED VEGETABLES` case end-to-end (not just the dedup step) would make the invariant verifiable and reduce the need for the warning."}],"totalDurationMs":138285,"totalTokens":59001,"totalToolUseCount":19,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":319,"cache_read_input_tokens":54070,"output_tokens":4611,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":319},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
