{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HPYA7eLe1orHqY39Ex7h1D","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a complete picture. Here is the review:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Test Quality — title-extractor (iteration 28)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 3 (test file, source, improvement plan) + eval script\n- Critical Gaps: 2\n- High Priority: 4\n- Medium Priority: 5\n- Suggestions: 3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe test suite has grown organically with the codebase and covers many important scenarios well, but every one of the four new mechanisms introduced in iterations 27-28 is untested at the unit level. The mock embed function's design makes it structurally incapable of distinguishing between two repair variants of the same text, which is precisely the signal needed for the dual-variant OCR repair logic. Additionally, `applyBlindOcrRepair` still calls `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"l\")` internally (line 881), so the `l`-variant produced by `generateBlindOcrVariants` is identical to what the old code produced — this latent bug is invisible without a direct assertion.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Gaps (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. Mock embed cannot differentiate OCR repair variants\n\n**Location:** `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:13-57`\n\n**Impact:** The dual-variant repair logic exists specifically so the embedding scorer picks the correct letter substitution. The mock embed resolves membership by `lower.includes(word)` against a flat list. If you test `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`, both the `i`-variant (`Braised Cod with White Wine`) and the `l`-variant (`Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne`) share no substring with the mock's `titleWords`. Both get the neutral vector `[0.3, 0.3, 0.7]`. The scorer cannot prefer one over the other — the test will be nondeterministic or pass for the wrong reason.\n\n**Root cause:** The mock was designed for the binary title/header distinction, not for comparing two near-identical candidates that differ by one letter substitution.\n\n**Solution:** For OCR-repair tests, add the repaired form as a title word and the corrupted form explicitly as a non-title word:\n\n```typescript\n// Creates a mock that rewards the i-variant over the l-variant\nconst embed = createMockEmbed(\n  [\"braised cod with white wine\"],   // i-variant matches → high title score\n  []\n);\n// \"Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne\" contains none of the title words → neutral score\n```\n\nThis works because `lower.includes(\"braised cod with white wine\")` will be true for `\"braised cod with white wine\"` (i-variant) and false for `\"bralsed cod wlth whlte wlne\"` (l-variant). The scorer will prefer the i-variant.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `applyBlindOcrRepair` still hardcodes `\"l\"` as the substitution letter\n\n**Location:** `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:881`\n\n**Impact:** `generateBlindOcrVariants` calls `applyBlindOcrRepair(text)` for the l-variant (line 928), which in the mixed-case path calls `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"l\")`. The improvement plan describes this as the original bug. The fix was supposed to be: generate both variants and let the embedder pick. Looking at the code, `generateBlindOcrVariants` does generate both variants correctly. However, `applyBlindOcrRepair` itself (the legacy function) still hardcodes `\"l\"` and is still called from `normalizeOcrTitle` at line 958. If the post-processing normalizer runs on a selected title that was already correctly repaired via the i-variant path, it may re-corrupt it back toward `\"l\"`.\n\n**Concrete scenario:** Candidate `Braised Cod with White Wine` scores best and wins. Then `normalizeOcrTitle` calls `repairOcrText → applyBlindOcrRepair` on the winner. If the winner had no remaining digits, no harm done. But if a digit survived (unlikely but possible), the legacy function would apply the wrong substitution.\n\nThere is no test that verifies the final output is the i-variant form rather than any intermediate representation.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"selects i-variant over l-variant for mixed-case OCR repair\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"braised cod with white wine\"], []);\n  const text = \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\\nIngredients\\n2 fillets\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Braised Cod with White Wine\");\n  // Explicitly verify the l-variant was NOT chosen:\n  expect(result).not.toContain(\"l\");  // \"Bralsed\", \"wlth\", etc.\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 3. No test for direct-successor bonus with intervening blank line\n\n**Location:** Test file has no test covering this. Source line 1156-1172.\n\n**Impact:** This is Fix 2 from the plan — three real failures (Halibut, Roasted Asparagus, Ogórkowa Zupa). The blank-line-skipping `while` loop is the fix. No test verifies it fires, so a future refactor that accidentally restores the direct `position - 1` check would go undetected.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"gives direct-successor bonus when section header is separated from title by a blank line\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"halibut with saffron cream sauce\"], []);\n  // FISH & SEAFOOD is a section label, blank line, then the title\n  const text = [\n    \"FISH & SEAFOOD\",\n    \"\",\n    \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"2 fillets\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\");\n});\n```\n\nA second variant covering the pipe-separated metadata predecessor (Ogórkowa Zupa pattern):\n```typescript\nit(\"gives direct-successor bonus when pipe-separated metadata precedes title across a blank line\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"ogórkowa zupa\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB\",\n    \"\",\n    \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\",\n    \"Składniki\",\n    \"3 ogórki\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. No test for broadened overflow marker regex\n\n**Location:** Test file has no overflow marker test at all. Source line 437 and 442.\n\n**Impact:** Fix 3 targets exactly one real case (Peach Cobbler). The regex change is isolated but fragile — a future regex tightening could silently regress it. The improvement plan explicitly calls out three distinct match paths: `CORRUPTED TEXT`, `PARTIAL RECIPE`, and the `[...]` bracketed annotation check.\n\n**Suggested tests:**\n```typescript\nit(\"skips [CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE] preamble to find real title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"peach cobbler\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]\",\n    \"some garbled spillover content here\",\n    \"more spillover\",\n    \"---\",\n    \"PEACH COBBLER\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"4 peaches\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"PEACH COBBLER\");\n});\n\nit(\"skips PREVIOUS PAGE overflow block introduced without brackets\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"apple tart\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"PREVIOUS PAGE OVERFLOW\",\n    \"some spillover text\",\n    \"\",\n    \"\",\n    \"APPLE TART\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"APPLE TART\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. No test for unified body-content prologue (interleaved instruction + prose)\n\n**Location:** Test file has `\"skips burst of short lines at start\"` (line 169) but that tests the garbled-characters burst, not the cooking-instruction/prose prologue. Source lines 483-504.\n\n**Impact:** Fix 4 is flagged as highest regression risk in the plan. The unified prologue check is a behavioral change from two separate checks with different thresholds to one combined check. No test exercises the interleaved pattern.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"skips interleaved cooking instruction and prose continuation prologue\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mushroom risotto\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock, one ladle at a time\",    // instruction\n    \"creamy but still al dente, about 18-20 minutes\",                      // prose continuation (lowercase start)\n    \"Season with salt and white pepper to taste\",                           // instruction\n    \"\",\n    \"MUSHROOM RISOTTO\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"300g arborio rice\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"MUSHROOM RISOTTO\");\n});\n```\n\nAlso needed — a regression test verifying the prologue detector does not fire on a legitimate recipe that opens with a single instruction followed by a title:\n```typescript\nit(\"does not skip prologue when fewer than 3 body-content lines precede title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"roast chicken\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"Preheat oven to 200°C\",    // one instruction line — below threshold\n    \"Roast Chicken\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"1 whole chicken\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Roast Chicken\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. No test for `hasErraticCasing` / `normalizeErraticCasing` path\n\n**Location:** Test file lacks any erratic casing input. Source lines 885-904.\n\n**Impact:** The `KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` failure is the only case triggering this path. The erratic casing detector has a nuanced threshold (`upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3`) that could be miscalibrated. There is no test confirming what `hasErraticCasing` returns for legitimate mixed-case words like `McDonald` or `iPhone`.\n\n**Suggested tests:**\n```typescript\nit(\"normalizes erratic casing before OCR repair (KoPyTka type)\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"kopytka z pieczarkami leśnymi\"], []);\n  // ¡ is an OCR artifact for i\n  const text = \"KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi\\nSkładniki\\n200g ziemniaków\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi\");\n});\n\nit(\"does not treat normal CamelCase as erratic (McDonald's type)\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mcdonald special sauce\"], []);\n  // \"McDonald's\" has upper M and upper D but only one uppercase after position 0\n  // — should not be flagged as erratic\n  const text = \"McDonald's Special Sauce\\nIngredients\\n2 tbsp mayo\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"McDonald's Special Sauce\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 7. `¡→i` and `€→e` substitutions are untested as standalone inputs\n\nThe `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` function handles `¡→i` and `€→e` substitutions explicitly (lines 855-856). The only place these characters could be tested is through `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`. Currently no test passes text containing `¡` or `€`. The `KoPyTka` test suggested above covers `¡` incidentally, but `€→e` is never tested at any level.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"repairs € to e in OCR-corrupted title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"creole chicken\"], []);\n  const text = \"Cr€ole Chicken\\nIngredients\\n1 whole chicken\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Creole Chicken\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 8. The `isTitleAbsentPage(lines, burstEnd)` integration is not exercised\n\nThe improvement plan notes this as a resolved design question (Open Question 3). `isTitleAbsentPage` now receives `burstEnd` as its second argument (source line 995) and slices from there. No test verifies this integration: a page where the first 3 lines are body prose (so `isTitleAbsentPage` would return true from position 0), but there IS a title after a prologue skip (so `isTitleAbsentPage` should return false from `burstEnd`). Without this test, the two mechanisms could be decoupled in a refactor.\n\n---\n\n### 9. The positional boost cap is not tested\n\nSource lines 1175-1182 cap the combined positional boost at `+0.15`. This cap affects the direct-successor bonus, position factor, and first-after-preamble bonus together. There is no test that exercises a scenario where multiple bonuses would fire simultaneously and verifies the cap prevents over-boosting. While this is internal scoring mechanics, it directly affects which candidate wins in ambiguous cases.\n\n---\n\n### 10. No negative test for overflow marker matching legitimate text\n\nThe broadened `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex now matches `PREVIOUS PAGE` without requiring `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT` after it. The plan acknowledges the risk: `\"see previous page for sauce base\"` in body text could trigger the marker. There is no test that verifies a recipe whose body text naturally contains \"previous page\" is not incorrectly skipped.\n\n---\n\n### 11. `ALL_CAPS` mode of `generateBlindOcrVariants` is not tested through public API\n\nThe `generateBlindOcrVariants` function has two branches: ALL_CAPS and mixed-case. The tests above (suggestions #2, #6) cover the mixed-case path. The ALL_CAPS path (`1→I`, `0→O`, `4→A`, `5→S`) is only exercised if an ALL_CAPS line at `index <= 5` also matches `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN`. No existing test provides an ALL_CAPS title with a digit.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"repairs digit artifacts in ALL_CAPS title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"roasted beet and walnut dip\"], []);\n  // \"1\" in ALL_CAPS context → \"I\"\n  const text = \"R0ASTED BEET AND WALNUT D1P\\nIngredients\\n3 beets\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"ROASTED BEET AND WALNUT DIP\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The existing tests are genuine scenario tests, not trivial input/output checks. Each describes a real OCR pathology with a comment explaining why it exists.\n- The corroboration suite (lines 391-480) is thorough and covers the three distinct cases: rejection, acceptance, and single-title bypass.\n- The `_resetEmbeddingCacheForTests` call in `beforeEach` correctly prevents cache contamination between tests.\n- The mock embed design (using dimension-per-concept vectors) is clean and predictable for the binary title-vs-header distinction it was built for.\n- Test names are specific and reference the real-world recipe pattern they protect (ARAYES-type, LABANEH-type, etc.), making regressions self-documenting.\n\n---\n\n## The Eval Suite (`eval_only.py`)\n\nThe script is functional and correctly used: it runs each fixture through the real `extract-title.ts` script, compares with OCR-normalized expected titles (stripping diacritics, normalizing digits), and reports pass/fail per file. This is the appropriate integration harness for iteration-level evaluation.\n\nOne gap worth noting: `titles_match` uses `_ocr_normalize` which maps `1→I`, `0→O`, `5→S` globally. This means a test where the extractor returns `Bra1sed Cod` would be normalized to `BRA1SED COD` → `BRAISED COD`, which would match the expected `BRAISED COD`. The eval would report a pass even though the extractor returned an unreduced title. For the purposes of the eval loop this is acceptable, but it means the eval script cannot catch the \"wrong repair letter selected\" failure mode that the unit test in suggestion #2 above would catch.\n\n---\n\n## Systemic Patterns\n\nTwo patterns appear across most gaps here: first, every fix is implemented and validated only at the eval level (11 real files), never at the unit test level. The unit test file has not grown in proportion to the function count. Second, the mock embed function has not been updated alongside the scoring logic it exercises — it was designed for iteration ~20 semantics and has not been adapted to reflect variant comparison, positional caps, or the prologue-skip interaction with `isTitleAbsentPage`. These are both candidates for a deliberate catch-up pass on the test file before iteration 29 changes land."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a3005ec533c46021a (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 44198\ntool_uses: 12\nduration_ms: 122558</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"66d6120a-7fee-4673-bb0a-75db3320d34d","uuid":"1e7cb25b-6a4a-41ff-b9b4-3e15ef2698c3","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review test quality for the title-extractor changes.\n\n## Context\nThe title extractor has been through 28 iterations of optimization. Changes include:\n1. Dual-variant blind OCR repair (i vs l variants)\n2. Direct-successor bonus skipping blank lines\n3. Broadened overflow marker regex\n4. Unified body-content prologue detector\n\n## Files to read\n- lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts — the unit test file\n- lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts — the source (to understand what's testable)\n- tools/title-loop/docs/28-1ac016c/improvement-plan.md — the plan (describes expected test cases)\n\n## Focus Areas\n1. **Coverage of new functions** — Are `hasErraticCasing`, `normalizeErraticCasing`, `generateBlindOcrVariants`, `applyBlindOcrRepair`, `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` tested? They're not exported, so they'd need to be tested through the public API.\n2. **Edge cases for OCR repair** — Does the test suite cover: mixed `i`/`l` ambiguity, erratic casing like `KoPyTka`, ALL_CAPS repair, `¡→i` and `€→e` substitution?\n3. **Prologue detection** — Are there tests for interleaved instruction/prose patterns? For the blank-line-skipping in the direct-successor bonus?\n4. **Overflow markers** — Tests for `[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]` style markers?\n5. **Regression protection** — Given this is iteration 28, are the existing tests comprehensive enough to catch regressions from the 4 changes?\n6. **The eval suite** — The plan mentions `eval_only.py` for integration testing. Check if `tools/title-loop/eval_only.py` exists and what it does.\n7. **Test structure** — Is the mock embed function adequate? Does it cover the scoring nuances needed for the new variant comparison logic?\n\nProvide specific gaps and suggestions for new test cases.","agentId":"a3005ec533c46021a","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have a complete picture. Here is the review:\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Test Quality — title-extractor (iteration 28)\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 3 (test file, source, improvement plan) + eval script\n- Critical Gaps: 2\n- High Priority: 4\n- Medium Priority: 5\n- Suggestions: 3\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe test suite has grown organically with the codebase and covers many important scenarios well, but every one of the four new mechanisms introduced in iterations 27-28 is untested at the unit level. The mock embed function's design makes it structurally incapable of distinguishing between two repair variants of the same text, which is precisely the signal needed for the dual-variant OCR repair logic. Additionally, `applyBlindOcrRepair` still calls `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"l\")` internally (line 881), so the `l`-variant produced by `generateBlindOcrVariants` is identical to what the old code produced — this latent bug is invisible without a direct assertion.\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL Gaps (Must Fix)\n\n### 1. Mock embed cannot differentiate OCR repair variants\n\n**Location:** `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:13-57`\n\n**Impact:** The dual-variant repair logic exists specifically so the embedding scorer picks the correct letter substitution. The mock embed resolves membership by `lower.includes(word)` against a flat list. If you test `Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne`, both the `i`-variant (`Braised Cod with White Wine`) and the `l`-variant (`Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne`) share no substring with the mock's `titleWords`. Both get the neutral vector `[0.3, 0.3, 0.7]`. The scorer cannot prefer one over the other — the test will be nondeterministic or pass for the wrong reason.\n\n**Root cause:** The mock was designed for the binary title/header distinction, not for comparing two near-identical candidates that differ by one letter substitution.\n\n**Solution:** For OCR-repair tests, add the repaired form as a title word and the corrupted form explicitly as a non-title word:\n\n```typescript\n// Creates a mock that rewards the i-variant over the l-variant\nconst embed = createMockEmbed(\n  [\"braised cod with white wine\"],   // i-variant matches → high title score\n  []\n);\n// \"Bralsed Cod wlth Whlte Wlne\" contains none of the title words → neutral score\n```\n\nThis works because `lower.includes(\"braised cod with white wine\")` will be true for `\"braised cod with white wine\"` (i-variant) and false for `\"bralsed cod wlth whlte wlne\"` (l-variant). The scorer will prefer the i-variant.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `applyBlindOcrRepair` still hardcodes `\"l\"` as the substitution letter\n\n**Location:** `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:881`\n\n**Impact:** `generateBlindOcrVariants` calls `applyBlindOcrRepair(text)` for the l-variant (line 928), which in the mixed-case path calls `applyBlindOcrRepairToken(token, \"l\")`. The improvement plan describes this as the original bug. The fix was supposed to be: generate both variants and let the embedder pick. Looking at the code, `generateBlindOcrVariants` does generate both variants correctly. However, `applyBlindOcrRepair` itself (the legacy function) still hardcodes `\"l\"` and is still called from `normalizeOcrTitle` at line 958. If the post-processing normalizer runs on a selected title that was already correctly repaired via the i-variant path, it may re-corrupt it back toward `\"l\"`.\n\n**Concrete scenario:** Candidate `Braised Cod with White Wine` scores best and wins. Then `normalizeOcrTitle` calls `repairOcrText → applyBlindOcrRepair` on the winner. If the winner had no remaining digits, no harm done. But if a digit survived (unlikely but possible), the legacy function would apply the wrong substitution.\n\nThere is no test that verifies the final output is the i-variant form rather than any intermediate representation.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"selects i-variant over l-variant for mixed-case OCR repair\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"braised cod with white wine\"], []);\n  const text = \"Bra1sed Cod w1th Wh1te W1ne\\nIngredients\\n2 fillets\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Braised Cod with White Wine\");\n  // Explicitly verify the l-variant was NOT chosen:\n  expect(result).not.toContain(\"l\");  // \"Bralsed\", \"wlth\", etc.\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority (Fix Before Merge)\n\n### 3. No test for direct-successor bonus with intervening blank line\n\n**Location:** Test file has no test covering this. Source line 1156-1172.\n\n**Impact:** This is Fix 2 from the plan — three real failures (Halibut, Roasted Asparagus, Ogórkowa Zupa). The blank-line-skipping `while` loop is the fix. No test verifies it fires, so a future refactor that accidentally restores the direct `position - 1` check would go undetected.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"gives direct-successor bonus when section header is separated from title by a blank line\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"halibut with saffron cream sauce\"], []);\n  // FISH & SEAFOOD is a section label, blank line, then the title\n  const text = [\n    \"FISH & SEAFOOD\",\n    \"\",\n    \"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"2 fillets\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Halibut with Saffron Cream Sauce\");\n});\n```\n\nA second variant covering the pipe-separated metadata predecessor (Ogórkowa Zupa pattern):\n```typescript\nit(\"gives direct-successor bonus when pipe-separated metadata precedes title across a blank line\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"ogórkowa zupa\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"Lato | Zupy | DLA 4 OSÓB\",\n    \"\",\n    \"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\",\n    \"Składniki\",\n    \"3 ogórki\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"OGÓRKOWA ZUPA\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. No test for broadened overflow marker regex\n\n**Location:** Test file has no overflow marker test at all. Source line 437 and 442.\n\n**Impact:** Fix 3 targets exactly one real case (Peach Cobbler). The regex change is isolated but fragile — a future regex tightening could silently regress it. The improvement plan explicitly calls out three distinct match paths: `CORRUPTED TEXT`, `PARTIAL RECIPE`, and the `[...]` bracketed annotation check.\n\n**Suggested tests:**\n```typescript\nit(\"skips [CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE] preamble to find real title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"peach cobbler\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"[CORRUPTED TEXT FROM PREVIOUS PAGE - PARTIAL RECIPE]\",\n    \"some garbled spillover content here\",\n    \"more spillover\",\n    \"---\",\n    \"PEACH COBBLER\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"4 peaches\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"PEACH COBBLER\");\n});\n\nit(\"skips PREVIOUS PAGE overflow block introduced without brackets\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"apple tart\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"PREVIOUS PAGE OVERFLOW\",\n    \"some spillover text\",\n    \"\",\n    \"\",\n    \"APPLE TART\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"APPLE TART\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. No test for unified body-content prologue (interleaved instruction + prose)\n\n**Location:** Test file has `\"skips burst of short lines at start\"` (line 169) but that tests the garbled-characters burst, not the cooking-instruction/prose prologue. Source lines 483-504.\n\n**Impact:** Fix 4 is flagged as highest regression risk in the plan. The unified prologue check is a behavioral change from two separate checks with different thresholds to one combined check. No test exercises the interleaved pattern.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"skips interleaved cooking instruction and prose continuation prologue\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mushroom risotto\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"Reduce heat and stir in the remaining stock, one ladle at a time\",    // instruction\n    \"creamy but still al dente, about 18-20 minutes\",                      // prose continuation (lowercase start)\n    \"Season with salt and white pepper to taste\",                           // instruction\n    \"\",\n    \"MUSHROOM RISOTTO\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"300g arborio rice\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"MUSHROOM RISOTTO\");\n});\n```\n\nAlso needed — a regression test verifying the prologue detector does not fire on a legitimate recipe that opens with a single instruction followed by a title:\n```typescript\nit(\"does not skip prologue when fewer than 3 body-content lines precede title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"roast chicken\"], []);\n  const text = [\n    \"Preheat oven to 200°C\",    // one instruction line — below threshold\n    \"Roast Chicken\",\n    \"Ingredients\",\n    \"1 whole chicken\",\n  ].join(\"\\n\");\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Roast Chicken\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 6. No test for `hasErraticCasing` / `normalizeErraticCasing` path\n\n**Location:** Test file lacks any erratic casing input. Source lines 885-904.\n\n**Impact:** The `KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi` failure is the only case triggering this path. The erratic casing detector has a nuanced threshold (`upperInner >= 2 && upperInner >= lowerInner * 0.3`) that could be miscalibrated. There is no test confirming what `hasErraticCasing` returns for legitimate mixed-case words like `McDonald` or `iPhone`.\n\n**Suggested tests:**\n```typescript\nit(\"normalizes erratic casing before OCR repair (KoPyTka type)\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"kopytka z pieczarkami leśnymi\"], []);\n  // ¡ is an OCR artifact for i\n  const text = \"KoPyTka z P¡eczarkami Leśnymi\\nSkładniki\\n200g ziemniaków\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Kopytka z Pieczarkami Leśnymi\");\n});\n\nit(\"does not treat normal CamelCase as erratic (McDonald's type)\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"mcdonald special sauce\"], []);\n  // \"McDonald's\" has upper M and upper D but only one uppercase after position 0\n  // — should not be flagged as erratic\n  const text = \"McDonald's Special Sauce\\nIngredients\\n2 tbsp mayo\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"McDonald's Special Sauce\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority (Fix Soon)\n\n### 7. `¡→i` and `€→e` substitutions are untested as standalone inputs\n\nThe `applyBlindOcrRepairToken` function handles `¡→i` and `€→e` substitutions explicitly (lines 855-856). The only place these characters could be tested is through `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`. Currently no test passes text containing `¡` or `€`. The `KoPyTka` test suggested above covers `¡` incidentally, but `€→e` is never tested at any level.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"repairs € to e in OCR-corrupted title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"creole chicken\"], []);\n  const text = \"Cr€ole Chicken\\nIngredients\\n1 whole chicken\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"Creole Chicken\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n### 8. The `isTitleAbsentPage(lines, burstEnd)` integration is not exercised\n\nThe improvement plan notes this as a resolved design question (Open Question 3). `isTitleAbsentPage` now receives `burstEnd` as its second argument (source line 995) and slices from there. No test verifies this integration: a page where the first 3 lines are body prose (so `isTitleAbsentPage` would return true from position 0), but there IS a title after a prologue skip (so `isTitleAbsentPage` should return false from `burstEnd`). Without this test, the two mechanisms could be decoupled in a refactor.\n\n---\n\n### 9. The positional boost cap is not tested\n\nSource lines 1175-1182 cap the combined positional boost at `+0.15`. This cap affects the direct-successor bonus, position factor, and first-after-preamble bonus together. There is no test that exercises a scenario where multiple bonuses would fire simultaneously and verifies the cap prevents over-boosting. While this is internal scoring mechanics, it directly affects which candidate wins in ambiguous cases.\n\n---\n\n### 10. No negative test for overflow marker matching legitimate text\n\nThe broadened `OVERFLOW_MARKERS` regex now matches `PREVIOUS PAGE` without requiring `OVERFLOW`/`CONTENT` after it. The plan acknowledges the risk: `\"see previous page for sauce base\"` in body text could trigger the marker. There is no test that verifies a recipe whose body text naturally contains \"previous page\" is not incorrectly skipped.\n\n---\n\n### 11. `ALL_CAPS` mode of `generateBlindOcrVariants` is not tested through public API\n\nThe `generateBlindOcrVariants` function has two branches: ALL_CAPS and mixed-case. The tests above (suggestions #2, #6) cover the mixed-case path. The ALL_CAPS path (`1→I`, `0→O`, `4→A`, `5→S`) is only exercised if an ALL_CAPS line at `index <= 5` also matches `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN`. No existing test provides an ALL_CAPS title with a digit.\n\n**Suggested test:**\n```typescript\nit(\"repairs digit artifacts in ALL_CAPS title\", async () => {\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"roasted beet and walnut dip\"], []);\n  // \"1\" in ALL_CAPS context → \"I\"\n  const text = \"R0ASTED BEET AND WALNUT D1P\\nIngredients\\n3 beets\";\n  const result = await extractTitleWithEmbeddings(text, embed);\n  expect(result).toBe(\"ROASTED BEET AND WALNUT DIP\");\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The existing tests are genuine scenario tests, not trivial input/output checks. Each describes a real OCR pathology with a comment explaining why it exists.\n- The corroboration suite (lines 391-480) is thorough and covers the three distinct cases: rejection, acceptance, and single-title bypass.\n- The `_resetEmbeddingCacheForTests` call in `beforeEach` correctly prevents cache contamination between tests.\n- The mock embed design (using dimension-per-concept vectors) is clean and predictable for the binary title-vs-header distinction it was built for.\n- Test names are specific and reference the real-world recipe pattern they protect (ARAYES-type, LABANEH-type, etc.), making regressions self-documenting.\n\n---\n\n## The Eval Suite (`eval_only.py`)\n\nThe script is functional and correctly used: it runs each fixture through the real `extract-title.ts` script, compares with OCR-normalized expected titles (stripping diacritics, normalizing digits), and reports pass/fail per file. This is the appropriate integration harness for iteration-level evaluation.\n\nOne gap worth noting: `titles_match` uses `_ocr_normalize` which maps `1→I`, `0→O`, `5→S` globally. This means a test where the extractor returns `Bra1sed Cod` would be normalized to `BRA1SED COD` → `BRAISED COD`, which would match the expected `BRAISED COD`. The eval would report a pass even though the extractor returned an unreduced title. For the purposes of the eval loop this is acceptable, but it means the eval script cannot catch the \"wrong repair letter selected\" failure mode that the unit test in suggestion #2 above would catch.\n\n---\n\n## Systemic Patterns\n\nTwo patterns appear across most gaps here: first, every fix is implemented and validated only at the eval level (11 real files), never at the unit test level. The unit test file has not grown in proportion to the function count. Second, the mock embed function has not been updated alongside the scoring logic it exercises — it was designed for iteration ~20 semantics and has not been adapted to reflect variant comparison, positional caps, or the prologue-skip interaction with `isTitleAbsentPage`. These are both candidates for a deliberate catch-up pass on the test file before iteration 29 changes land."}],"totalDurationMs":122558,"totalTokens":44198,"totalToolUseCount":12,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1542,"cache_read_input_tokens":38097,"output_tokens":4558,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1542},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
