{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01BGAEdezNUxJg1jisKfTg9G","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a thorough analysis. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance Analysis — title-extractor.ts\n\n## Review Metrics\n- **Files Reviewed**: 1 (1,662 lines)\n- **Critical Issues**: 0\n- **High Priority**: 2\n- **Medium Priority**: 3\n- **Low Priority / Observations**: 4\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe pipeline is correct and the 25-candidate cap is the most important safeguard for embed-call budget. However, there are two real mobile performance risks: `passesCorroboration` is called multiple times and each call runs an O(words × lines) inner loop that is not guarded against long documents, and `repairOcrText` (which itself iterates words and may explode into exponential substitution variants per word) runs three times per candidate in the hot candidate-building loop. The `hasErraticCasing` redundant calls and string-operation volume are minor on typical inputs but worth closing.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `passesCorroboration` — called twice with no memoization, on potentially large `lines` arrays\n\n**Files**: `title-extractor.ts:1344`, `title-extractor.ts:1547`\n\n**What**: `passesCorroboration` is invoked twice in `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` — once at line 1344 on all ALL_CAPS scored candidates (pre-threshold artifact filter) and again at line 1547 on the same or overlapping set (multi-title guard). There is no memoization between the two calls. Each call runs an inner loop: for every content word in the candidate, scan all lines from `startLine` to end checking `.toUpperCase().includes(word)`. That is O(contentWords × lines) per candidate.\n\n**Root Cause**: The function was designed for correctness at each call site but was added incrementally, so the two call sites don't share results.\n\n**Impact on mobile**: A document with 100 non-empty lines and a candidate with 5 content words costs 500 string operations per `passesCorroboration` call. With up to 25 ALL_CAPS candidates, worst case is 25 × 2 × 500 = 25,000 `.toUpperCase()` + `.includes()` calls — each operating on potentially long strings. This is synchronous CPU work that cannot be parallelised. On a mid-range mobile CPU this will register as a visible stall (tens of milliseconds).\n\nAdditionally, `.toUpperCase()` is called on every line for every word on every invocation. The lines array is never pre-uppercased.\n\n**Solution**:\n\n```typescript\n// Pre-uppercase lines once, outside passesCorroboration\nconst upperLines = lines.map(l => l.toUpperCase());\n\n// Revised signature — accepts pre-uppercased lines to skip per-call work\nfunction passesCorroboration(\n  text: string,\n  position: number,\n  upperLines: string[],\n  startLine: number = 0\n): boolean {\n  const contentWords = extractContentWords(text); // already returns .toUpperCase()\n  if (contentWords.length === 0) return true;\n\n  let corroboratedCount = 0;\n  for (const word of contentWords) {\n    for (let i = startLine; i < upperLines.length; i++) {\n      if (i === position) continue;\n      if (upperLines[i].includes(word)) {\n        corroboratedCount++;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  const score = corroboratedCount / contentWords.length;\n  return score >= (contentWords.length <= 3 ? 1.0 : 0.67);\n}\n```\n\nThen memoize results between the two call sites using the candidate text as a key:\n\n```typescript\nconst corroborationCache = new Map<string, boolean>();\nfunction cachedPassesCorroboration(text: string, position: number, upperLines: string[], startLine: number) {\n  const key = `${text}|${position}`;\n  if (!corroborationCache.has(key)) {\n    corroborationCache.set(key, passesCorroboration(text, position, upperLines, startLine));\n  }\n  return corroborationCache.get(key)!;\n}\n```\n\nThis turns the two-pass 25,000-operation scenario into a single 12,500-operation pass with O(1) lookups for the second call site.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `repairOcrText` called three times per candidate line in the hot loop\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:648`, `689`, `703`\n\n**What**: Inside the `buildCandidates` loop, for every line `i` of `mergedLines`:\n- Line 648: `repairOcrText(...)` for the single candidate\n- Line 689: `repairOcrText(line.text + \" \" + mergedLines[i+1].text)` for the 2-line join\n- Line 703: `repairOcrText(line.text + \" \" + mergedLines[i+1].text + \" \" + mergedLines[i+2].text)` for the 3-line join\n\n`repairOcrText` itself calls `.split(/\\s+/)`, then for each word calls `repairOcrWord`, which may call `generateSubstitutions` (recursive, up to 2^8 = 256 variants per word if there are 8 OCR artifact positions). For a 10-word joined candidate with 3 artifact-bearing words, this is roughly `3 × 2^3 = 24` dictionary lookups per word per join candidate. Across three calls per line and N lines, this compounds quickly.\n\n**Root Cause**: The join candidates are assembled as raw strings and each independently fed to `repairOcrText`, so the repair work on shared prefixes (`line.text`) is done three times.\n\n**Impact on mobile**: For a 20-line document, the loop runs 20 iterations, each performing three `repairOcrText` calls. That is 60 calls with substring concatenation allocations, regex splits, and exponential variant expansion in the worst case. The exponential guard `positions.length > 8` prevents runaway, but 4–6 artifact positions per word (yielding 16–64 variants each) on a 10-word title still represent hundreds of dictionary lookups per call.\n\n**Solution**: Cache the per-line repair result and reuse it in join assembly:\n\n```typescript\n// In buildCandidates loop — compute per-line repaired text once\nconst repaired: Map<number, string> = new Map();\nfunction getRepaired(i: number): string {\n  if (!repaired.has(i)) {\n    repaired.set(i, repairOcrText(mergedLines[i].text));\n  }\n  return repaired.get(i)!;\n}\n\n// Single\nconst singleText = stripParentheticalGloss(stripPageNumber(getRepaired(i)));\n\n// 2-line join — combine already-repaired parts (no re-repair needed since repair is word-level)\nif (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n  const joined2 = `${getRepaired(i)} ${getRepaired(i + 1)}`;\n  // ...\n}\n\n// 3-line join\nif (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n  const joined3 = `${getRepaired(i)} ${getRepaired(i + 1)} ${getRepaired(i + 2)}`;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nNote: joining pre-repaired words is semantically equivalent since `repairOcrText` operates word-by-word with no cross-word context. This reduces O(3N) repair calls to O(N).\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. `passesCorroboration` `startLine` parameter — shifts window but does not reduce O(n)\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:257`\n\n**What**: The `startLine` parameter was added to skip overflow preamble lines from the corroboration scan. The comment says it reduces work. It does shift the scan start, but the worst-case complexity remains O(contentWords × (lines.length - startLine)). On a 200-line document where `burstEnd` is 5, the parameter saves 5 iterations out of 200 — a 2.5% reduction.\n\n**Root Cause**: The parameter is documented as \"only check corroboration against lines from this index onward\" but this is semantically the intent (skip contaminating preamble), not a performance optimisation in any meaningful sense.\n\n**Impact**: Not a regression, but the current code comments and architecture imply it is a meaningful performance guard — it is not. If documents grow longer (e.g. multi-page OCR batches), this will not protect against slow corroboration.\n\n**Realistic ceiling**: If you know typical OCR output is capped at ~60 lines per recipe photo, the O(n × m) is bounded at ~60 × 5 × 25 = 7,500 operations per full `passesCorroboration` run, which is fine. The concern only materialises if the caller ever passes multi-page document text. Confirm that the input to `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` is single-page. If it is, document this assumption explicitly and add a defensive line-count guard at the entry point:\n\n```typescript\n// Guard against multi-page batches being accidentally passed in\nconst MAX_LINES = 80;\nconst lines = text.split(\"\\n\").slice(0, MAX_LINES);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `hasErraticCasing` called redundantly in `buildCandidates`\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:662`, `664`\n\n**What**: At line 662, `hasErraticCasing(line.text)` is called as the OR-condition of the `if`. If that branch is entered, line 664 calls `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` again. At this point `repairable === singleText` which is `repairOcrText(line.text)`. In the common case where `repairOcrText` makes no changes (no OCR artifacts in the text), `repairable === line.text` and the second call is an exact duplicate.\n\nAdditionally, `normalizeErraticCasing` (line 897, inside the function) calls `hasErraticCasing` on each token again internally, making it a third call on the same data.\n\n**Root Cause**: Incremental logic additions without a unified \"classify this line once\" step at the top of the loop body.\n\n**Solution**: Compute all per-line properties at the top of the loop and reuse them:\n\n```typescript\nfor (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n  const line = mergedLines[i];\n  const hasArtifacts = OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text);\n  const hasCasing = line.index <= 5 && hasErraticCasing(line.text);\n  const singleText = repairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripPageNumber(line.text)));\n\n  // ...single candidate logic...\n\n  if (line.index <= 5 && (hasArtifacts || hasCasing)) {\n    let repairable = singleText;\n    if (hasCasing) { // already computed — no second call\n      repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n      // ...\n    }\n    // ...\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `findBurstEnd` overflow-marker scan — O(n²) nested loops up to depth 30\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:439–473`\n\n**What**: The outer loop runs up to `k = 30` iterations. For each overflow marker found, the inner `while (m < lines.length)` loop scans forward through the entire remaining document. In the worst case (every line for the first 30 lines is an overflow marker, document is 200 lines), this is 30 × 200 = 6,000 iterations. This is bounded and harmless on typical inputs, but the `overflowEnd = 0` reset on line 471 means if the inner loop reaches end-of-document without finding a terminator, `overflowEnd` could be re-overwritten by the next outer iteration's scan — which would restart the inner scan from scratch. The `if (overflowEnd > 0 && k < overflowEnd) continue;` guard at line 441 partially protects this but only when `overflowEnd` has been set. On a pathological document of 30 consecutive overflow-marker lines, the inner loop runs 30 times from varying starting positions.\n\n**Impact**: Bounded to 30 × N, acceptable for single-page input. Not a regression, but the condition at line 471 (`if (overflowEnd === 0) overflowEnd = m`) can assign `overflowEnd = lines.length` on the first iteration, causing all 30 outer iterations to be skipped via the line 441 guard — this is actually the correct protective behaviour. The logic is sound but subtle.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Observations\n\n### 6. Worst-case embed call count analysis\n\nThe 25-candidate cap is the dominant safeguard. Here is the worst-case trace:\n\n- Input: 20 non-empty lines, none filtered by `passesHardFilters`, first 5 qualifying for blind OCR variants\n- Per line: 1 single + 1 two-line join + 1 three-line join = 3 candidates/line → 60 raw candidates\n- Per early line (index ≤ 5): up to 2 blind OCR variants added → 5 lines × 2 variants = 10 extra\n- Total raw: 60 + 10 = 70 candidates, deduplicated by `seen` Set, then capped to 25 before the embed loop\n- Reference embeddings: 3 (cached after first call, so 3 on first invocation, 0 on subsequent)\n- Total embed calls: **25 candidates + 3 references = 28 on first invocation, 25 on subsequent**\n\nThis is the correct worst case regardless of how many OCR variant candidates are generated — the cap at line 718 absorbs all of them. The OCR variant path cannot inflate the embed count beyond 25.\n\nAt a generous 300ms per embed call (on-device model) this is 7.5 seconds for 25 candidates. Tight but within the 10-second budget if processing starts promptly and the reference embeddings were cached from a prior call. At 400ms per call (slow network round-trip) this is exactly 10 seconds — no margin. The cap is the right lever to adjust if profiling shows embed calls are the bottleneck.\n\n### 7. `passesHardFilters` calls `looksLikeMetadata` which iterates 17+ regex patterns per call\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:226–228`, `385–426`\n\n`passesHardFilters` is called once per single candidate, once per 2-line join, once per 3-line join, plus once more per blind OCR variant — roughly 4 times per line. Each call executes `METADATA_PATTERNS.some(p => p.test(text))` which can test up to 17 regexes. This is O(4 × N_lines × 17_patterns) = O(68 × N). For 20 lines that is 1,360 regex tests, all synchronous. This is small but worth noting: the 17 METADATA_PATTERNS include two global patterns (`/\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b/i` and `/\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ/i`) with word-boundary anchors, which are slightly more expensive than start-anchored patterns on V8/Hermes. Not a problem in isolation; mentioned because it compounds with the join-candidate explosion if the 25-candidate cap were ever removed.\n\n### 8. `capsCoalesced` merge loop calls `isSectionLabel` and `looksLikeMetadata` on every line pair\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:567–605`\n\nInside the coalescing while-loop at line 579, `isSectionLabel` and `looksLikeMetadata` are called on `next.text` every iteration. `isSectionLabel` calls `stripDiacritics` (NFKD normalization + regex replace) and does two Set lookups. `looksLikeMetadata` runs 17 regexes. For a document where every line is short ALL_CAPS (worst case for the coalescing loop), this loop runs O(N²/2) times. In practice this is bounded to short inputs by the `wordCount <= 2 && length <= 25` guard, but the O(N²) worst case is real if those conditions are met throughout.\n\n**This is a pre-existing O(N²) risk, not introduced by the changes under review.**\n\n### 9. String allocations in the join candidate path\n\nAt lines 689 and 703, template literals create new strings by concatenating potentially-repaired line texts. After caching repairs (see Issue 2), these become simple string concats, which is fine. The `.toLowerCase()` calls on joined candidates for the `seen` Set deduplication (lines 692, 707) create additional temporary strings. These are unavoidable but should be noted as allocation pressure in the loop. On Hermes (React Native's JS engine) string interning behavior differs from V8, so allocation-heavy loops have higher GC pressure than they would in Node.js benchmarks.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The 25-candidate pre-filter before the embed loop (line 718) is the correct architectural decision and tightly controls the most expensive operation.\n- Reference embedding caching (module-level `cachedTitleRefEmbedding` etc.) correctly eliminates 3 redundant embed calls on subsequent invocations.\n- The `seen` Set deduplication prevents embed calls on textually identical candidates produced by different join paths.\n- The `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` fast-path at line 662 gates the expensive `generateBlindOcrVariants` path behind a cheap regex test, avoiding unnecessary work on clean text.\n- Blind OCR variant generation is correctly capped: `generateBlindOcrVariants` returns at most 2 variants for mixed-case text and at most 1 for ALL_CAPS, so the maximum per-line contribution to the candidate pool is 3 (1 original + 2 variants), matching the analysis in Issue 6.\n\n## Summary of Actionable Items\n\n| Priority | Issue | Estimated Mobile Savings |\n|---|---|---|\n| HIGH | Pre-uppercase lines once; memoize `passesCorroboration` across both call sites | ~15–30ms on 100-line doc |\n| HIGH | Cache per-line `repairOcrText` result; assemble joins from cached parts | ~10–20ms on 20-line doc |\n| MEDIUM | Document/enforce single-page input assumption; add defensive line-count guard | Prevents O(n²) on multi-page input |\n| MEDIUM | Compute `hasErraticCasing` once per line, not 2–3 times | ~1–2ms; mostly code clarity |\n| LOW | Everything else above | Negligible individually |\n\nNone of the issues above are regressions introduced in isolation — they are cumulative effects of incrementally added logic. The two HIGH items are the only ones with meaningful wall-clock impact on a real device. Both are localised changes with no semantic effect on output."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: add445ad01d7f7acf (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 49850\ntool_uses: 14\nduration_ms: 146861</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"66d6120a-7fee-4673-bb0a-75db3320d34d","uuid":"7b80e4f4-002e-4039-a00d-80556bf4e1c4","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Analyze performance of the changes in lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts.\n\n## Critical Constraint\nThis code runs on a MOBILE DEVICE (React Native / Expo). Total title extraction must complete under 10 seconds. The bottleneck is embedding computation (each embed call = network round-trip or on-device model inference).\n\n## Changes to analyze\nRead the file and focus on:\n\n1. **Extra candidates from OCR variants** — `generateBlindOcrVariants` adds up to 2 variants per line for the first 5 lines. That's up to 10 extra candidates. With a 25-candidate cap, what's the worst-case embed call count? Each candidate needs 1 embedding.\n2. **The unified prologue detector** — `while` loop scanning lines at start. Any risk of O(n) scanning on very long documents?\n3. **Direct-successor bonus** — backward scanning with `while (prevPos >= 0 && lines[prevPos].trim() === \"\")`. Bounded? Could blank-heavy documents cause issues?\n4. **`passesCorroboration` with `startLine`** — Still O(words × lines) inner loop. Is the `startLine` parameter actually reducing work or just shifting the window?\n5. **`hasErraticCasing` called multiple times** — Called in `buildCandidates` condition AND inside the block AND in `normalizeOcrTitle`. Are there redundant calls?\n6. **String operations** — `.split(/\\s+/)`, regex matching, `.toUpperCase()`, `.toLowerCase()` on potentially many lines. Are these hot paths?\n7. **Overall candidate pipeline** — trace the worst-case path: max lines → max candidates → max embed calls → total time.\n\nFocus on real mobile performance concerns, not theoretical optimization.","agentId":"add445ad01d7f7acf","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I now have everything I need for a thorough analysis. Let me compile the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: Performance Analysis — title-extractor.ts\n\n## Review Metrics\n- **Files Reviewed**: 1 (1,662 lines)\n- **Critical Issues**: 0\n- **High Priority**: 2\n- **Medium Priority**: 3\n- **Low Priority / Observations**: 4\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe pipeline is correct and the 25-candidate cap is the most important safeguard for embed-call budget. However, there are two real mobile performance risks: `passesCorroboration` is called multiple times and each call runs an O(words × lines) inner loop that is not guarded against long documents, and `repairOcrText` (which itself iterates words and may explode into exponential substitution variants per word) runs three times per candidate in the hot candidate-building loop. The `hasErraticCasing` redundant calls and string-operation volume are minor on typical inputs but worth closing.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. `passesCorroboration` — called twice with no memoization, on potentially large `lines` arrays\n\n**Files**: `title-extractor.ts:1344`, `title-extractor.ts:1547`\n\n**What**: `passesCorroboration` is invoked twice in `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` — once at line 1344 on all ALL_CAPS scored candidates (pre-threshold artifact filter) and again at line 1547 on the same or overlapping set (multi-title guard). There is no memoization between the two calls. Each call runs an inner loop: for every content word in the candidate, scan all lines from `startLine` to end checking `.toUpperCase().includes(word)`. That is O(contentWords × lines) per candidate.\n\n**Root Cause**: The function was designed for correctness at each call site but was added incrementally, so the two call sites don't share results.\n\n**Impact on mobile**: A document with 100 non-empty lines and a candidate with 5 content words costs 500 string operations per `passesCorroboration` call. With up to 25 ALL_CAPS candidates, worst case is 25 × 2 × 500 = 25,000 `.toUpperCase()` + `.includes()` calls — each operating on potentially long strings. This is synchronous CPU work that cannot be parallelised. On a mid-range mobile CPU this will register as a visible stall (tens of milliseconds).\n\nAdditionally, `.toUpperCase()` is called on every line for every word on every invocation. The lines array is never pre-uppercased.\n\n**Solution**:\n\n```typescript\n// Pre-uppercase lines once, outside passesCorroboration\nconst upperLines = lines.map(l => l.toUpperCase());\n\n// Revised signature — accepts pre-uppercased lines to skip per-call work\nfunction passesCorroboration(\n  text: string,\n  position: number,\n  upperLines: string[],\n  startLine: number = 0\n): boolean {\n  const contentWords = extractContentWords(text); // already returns .toUpperCase()\n  if (contentWords.length === 0) return true;\n\n  let corroboratedCount = 0;\n  for (const word of contentWords) {\n    for (let i = startLine; i < upperLines.length; i++) {\n      if (i === position) continue;\n      if (upperLines[i].includes(word)) {\n        corroboratedCount++;\n        break;\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  const score = corroboratedCount / contentWords.length;\n  return score >= (contentWords.length <= 3 ? 1.0 : 0.67);\n}\n```\n\nThen memoize results between the two call sites using the candidate text as a key:\n\n```typescript\nconst corroborationCache = new Map<string, boolean>();\nfunction cachedPassesCorroboration(text: string, position: number, upperLines: string[], startLine: number) {\n  const key = `${text}|${position}`;\n  if (!corroborationCache.has(key)) {\n    corroborationCache.set(key, passesCorroboration(text, position, upperLines, startLine));\n  }\n  return corroborationCache.get(key)!;\n}\n```\n\nThis turns the two-pass 25,000-operation scenario into a single 12,500-operation pass with O(1) lookups for the second call site.\n\n---\n\n### 2. `repairOcrText` called three times per candidate line in the hot loop\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:648`, `689`, `703`\n\n**What**: Inside the `buildCandidates` loop, for every line `i` of `mergedLines`:\n- Line 648: `repairOcrText(...)` for the single candidate\n- Line 689: `repairOcrText(line.text + \" \" + mergedLines[i+1].text)` for the 2-line join\n- Line 703: `repairOcrText(line.text + \" \" + mergedLines[i+1].text + \" \" + mergedLines[i+2].text)` for the 3-line join\n\n`repairOcrText` itself calls `.split(/\\s+/)`, then for each word calls `repairOcrWord`, which may call `generateSubstitutions` (recursive, up to 2^8 = 256 variants per word if there are 8 OCR artifact positions). For a 10-word joined candidate with 3 artifact-bearing words, this is roughly `3 × 2^3 = 24` dictionary lookups per word per join candidate. Across three calls per line and N lines, this compounds quickly.\n\n**Root Cause**: The join candidates are assembled as raw strings and each independently fed to `repairOcrText`, so the repair work on shared prefixes (`line.text`) is done three times.\n\n**Impact on mobile**: For a 20-line document, the loop runs 20 iterations, each performing three `repairOcrText` calls. That is 60 calls with substring concatenation allocations, regex splits, and exponential variant expansion in the worst case. The exponential guard `positions.length > 8` prevents runaway, but 4–6 artifact positions per word (yielding 16–64 variants each) on a 10-word title still represent hundreds of dictionary lookups per call.\n\n**Solution**: Cache the per-line repair result and reuse it in join assembly:\n\n```typescript\n// In buildCandidates loop — compute per-line repaired text once\nconst repaired: Map<number, string> = new Map();\nfunction getRepaired(i: number): string {\n  if (!repaired.has(i)) {\n    repaired.set(i, repairOcrText(mergedLines[i].text));\n  }\n  return repaired.get(i)!;\n}\n\n// Single\nconst singleText = stripParentheticalGloss(stripPageNumber(getRepaired(i)));\n\n// 2-line join — combine already-repaired parts (no re-repair needed since repair is word-level)\nif (i + 1 < mergedLines.length) {\n  const joined2 = `${getRepaired(i)} ${getRepaired(i + 1)}`;\n  // ...\n}\n\n// 3-line join\nif (i + 2 < mergedLines.length) {\n  const joined3 = `${getRepaired(i)} ${getRepaired(i + 1)} ${getRepaired(i + 2)}`;\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\nNote: joining pre-repaired words is semantically equivalent since `repairOcrText` operates word-by-word with no cross-word context. This reduces O(3N) repair calls to O(N).\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 3. `passesCorroboration` `startLine` parameter — shifts window but does not reduce O(n)\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:257`\n\n**What**: The `startLine` parameter was added to skip overflow preamble lines from the corroboration scan. The comment says it reduces work. It does shift the scan start, but the worst-case complexity remains O(contentWords × (lines.length - startLine)). On a 200-line document where `burstEnd` is 5, the parameter saves 5 iterations out of 200 — a 2.5% reduction.\n\n**Root Cause**: The parameter is documented as \"only check corroboration against lines from this index onward\" but this is semantically the intent (skip contaminating preamble), not a performance optimisation in any meaningful sense.\n\n**Impact**: Not a regression, but the current code comments and architecture imply it is a meaningful performance guard — it is not. If documents grow longer (e.g. multi-page OCR batches), this will not protect against slow corroboration.\n\n**Realistic ceiling**: If you know typical OCR output is capped at ~60 lines per recipe photo, the O(n × m) is bounded at ~60 × 5 × 25 = 7,500 operations per full `passesCorroboration` run, which is fine. The concern only materialises if the caller ever passes multi-page document text. Confirm that the input to `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` is single-page. If it is, document this assumption explicitly and add a defensive line-count guard at the entry point:\n\n```typescript\n// Guard against multi-page batches being accidentally passed in\nconst MAX_LINES = 80;\nconst lines = text.split(\"\\n\").slice(0, MAX_LINES);\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. `hasErraticCasing` called redundantly in `buildCandidates`\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:662`, `664`\n\n**What**: At line 662, `hasErraticCasing(line.text)` is called as the OR-condition of the `if`. If that branch is entered, line 664 calls `hasErraticCasing(repairable)` again. At this point `repairable === singleText` which is `repairOcrText(line.text)`. In the common case where `repairOcrText` makes no changes (no OCR artifacts in the text), `repairable === line.text` and the second call is an exact duplicate.\n\nAdditionally, `normalizeErraticCasing` (line 897, inside the function) calls `hasErraticCasing` on each token again internally, making it a third call on the same data.\n\n**Root Cause**: Incremental logic additions without a unified \"classify this line once\" step at the top of the loop body.\n\n**Solution**: Compute all per-line properties at the top of the loop and reuse them:\n\n```typescript\nfor (let i = 0; i < mergedLines.length; i++) {\n  const line = mergedLines[i];\n  const hasArtifacts = OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN.test(line.text);\n  const hasCasing = line.index <= 5 && hasErraticCasing(line.text);\n  const singleText = repairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripPageNumber(line.text)));\n\n  // ...single candidate logic...\n\n  if (line.index <= 5 && (hasArtifacts || hasCasing)) {\n    let repairable = singleText;\n    if (hasCasing) { // already computed — no second call\n      repairable = normalizeErraticCasing(repairable);\n      // ...\n    }\n    // ...\n  }\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. `findBurstEnd` overflow-marker scan — O(n²) nested loops up to depth 30\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:439–473`\n\n**What**: The outer loop runs up to `k = 30` iterations. For each overflow marker found, the inner `while (m < lines.length)` loop scans forward through the entire remaining document. In the worst case (every line for the first 30 lines is an overflow marker, document is 200 lines), this is 30 × 200 = 6,000 iterations. This is bounded and harmless on typical inputs, but the `overflowEnd = 0` reset on line 471 means if the inner loop reaches end-of-document without finding a terminator, `overflowEnd` could be re-overwritten by the next outer iteration's scan — which would restart the inner scan from scratch. The `if (overflowEnd > 0 && k < overflowEnd) continue;` guard at line 441 partially protects this but only when `overflowEnd` has been set. On a pathological document of 30 consecutive overflow-marker lines, the inner loop runs 30 times from varying starting positions.\n\n**Impact**: Bounded to 30 × N, acceptable for single-page input. Not a regression, but the condition at line 471 (`if (overflowEnd === 0) overflowEnd = m`) can assign `overflowEnd = lines.length` on the first iteration, causing all 30 outer iterations to be skipped via the line 441 guard — this is actually the correct protective behaviour. The logic is sound but subtle.\n\n---\n\n## LOW Priority / Observations\n\n### 6. Worst-case embed call count analysis\n\nThe 25-candidate cap is the dominant safeguard. Here is the worst-case trace:\n\n- Input: 20 non-empty lines, none filtered by `passesHardFilters`, first 5 qualifying for blind OCR variants\n- Per line: 1 single + 1 two-line join + 1 three-line join = 3 candidates/line → 60 raw candidates\n- Per early line (index ≤ 5): up to 2 blind OCR variants added → 5 lines × 2 variants = 10 extra\n- Total raw: 60 + 10 = 70 candidates, deduplicated by `seen` Set, then capped to 25 before the embed loop\n- Reference embeddings: 3 (cached after first call, so 3 on first invocation, 0 on subsequent)\n- Total embed calls: **25 candidates + 3 references = 28 on first invocation, 25 on subsequent**\n\nThis is the correct worst case regardless of how many OCR variant candidates are generated — the cap at line 718 absorbs all of them. The OCR variant path cannot inflate the embed count beyond 25.\n\nAt a generous 300ms per embed call (on-device model) this is 7.5 seconds for 25 candidates. Tight but within the 10-second budget if processing starts promptly and the reference embeddings were cached from a prior call. At 400ms per call (slow network round-trip) this is exactly 10 seconds — no margin. The cap is the right lever to adjust if profiling shows embed calls are the bottleneck.\n\n### 7. `passesHardFilters` calls `looksLikeMetadata` which iterates 17+ regex patterns per call\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:226–228`, `385–426`\n\n`passesHardFilters` is called once per single candidate, once per 2-line join, once per 3-line join, plus once more per blind OCR variant — roughly 4 times per line. Each call executes `METADATA_PATTERNS.some(p => p.test(text))` which can test up to 17 regexes. This is O(4 × N_lines × 17_patterns) = O(68 × N). For 20 lines that is 1,360 regex tests, all synchronous. This is small but worth noting: the 17 METADATA_PATTERNS include two global patterns (`/\\b\\d+\\s*MIN\\b/i` and `/\\b\\d+\\s*GODZ/i`) with word-boundary anchors, which are slightly more expensive than start-anchored patterns on V8/Hermes. Not a problem in isolation; mentioned because it compounds with the join-candidate explosion if the 25-candidate cap were ever removed.\n\n### 8. `capsCoalesced` merge loop calls `isSectionLabel` and `looksLikeMetadata` on every line pair\n\n**File**: `title-extractor.ts:567–605`\n\nInside the coalescing while-loop at line 579, `isSectionLabel` and `looksLikeMetadata` are called on `next.text` every iteration. `isSectionLabel` calls `stripDiacritics` (NFKD normalization + regex replace) and does two Set lookups. `looksLikeMetadata` runs 17 regexes. For a document where every line is short ALL_CAPS (worst case for the coalescing loop), this loop runs O(N²/2) times. In practice this is bounded to short inputs by the `wordCount <= 2 && length <= 25` guard, but the O(N²) worst case is real if those conditions are met throughout.\n\n**This is a pre-existing O(N²) risk, not introduced by the changes under review.**\n\n### 9. String allocations in the join candidate path\n\nAt lines 689 and 703, template literals create new strings by concatenating potentially-repaired line texts. After caching repairs (see Issue 2), these become simple string concats, which is fine. The `.toLowerCase()` calls on joined candidates for the `seen` Set deduplication (lines 692, 707) create additional temporary strings. These are unavoidable but should be noted as allocation pressure in the loop. On Hermes (React Native's JS engine) string interning behavior differs from V8, so allocation-heavy loops have higher GC pressure than they would in Node.js benchmarks.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The 25-candidate pre-filter before the embed loop (line 718) is the correct architectural decision and tightly controls the most expensive operation.\n- Reference embedding caching (module-level `cachedTitleRefEmbedding` etc.) correctly eliminates 3 redundant embed calls on subsequent invocations.\n- The `seen` Set deduplication prevents embed calls on textually identical candidates produced by different join paths.\n- The `OCR_ARTIFACT_PATTERN` fast-path at line 662 gates the expensive `generateBlindOcrVariants` path behind a cheap regex test, avoiding unnecessary work on clean text.\n- Blind OCR variant generation is correctly capped: `generateBlindOcrVariants` returns at most 2 variants for mixed-case text and at most 1 for ALL_CAPS, so the maximum per-line contribution to the candidate pool is 3 (1 original + 2 variants), matching the analysis in Issue 6.\n\n## Summary of Actionable Items\n\n| Priority | Issue | Estimated Mobile Savings |\n|---|---|---|\n| HIGH | Pre-uppercase lines once; memoize `passesCorroboration` across both call sites | ~15–30ms on 100-line doc |\n| HIGH | Cache per-line `repairOcrText` result; assemble joins from cached parts | ~10–20ms on 20-line doc |\n| MEDIUM | Document/enforce single-page input assumption; add defensive line-count guard | Prevents O(n²) on multi-page input |\n| MEDIUM | Compute `hasErraticCasing` once per line, not 2–3 times | ~1–2ms; mostly code clarity |\n| LOW | Everything else above | Negligible individually |\n\nNone of the issues above are regressions introduced in isolation — they are cumulative effects of incrementally added logic. The two HIGH items are the only ones with meaningful wall-clock impact on a real device. Both are localised changes with no semantic effect on output."}],"totalDurationMs":146861,"totalTokens":49850,"totalToolUseCount":14,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":528,"cache_read_input_tokens":44632,"output_tokens":4689,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":528},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
